@0    = ~It's been a long time since we sat beside the fire together. How are you holding up?~ [bgav102]
@1    = ~I've been kidnapped, held against my will, and tortured. You?~
@2    = ~About as well as can be expected, really.~
@3    = ~They captured Imoen, Gavin. They took her to a prison for magical deviants, and I don't even know where it is.~
@4    = ~Dynaheir and Khalid are dead. Dynaheir might have died during my capture, but Khalid was flayed alive.~
@5    = ~I'm on another quest to save the world, and I don't even have a soul.~
@6    = ~It's terrible, Gavin. I've had no one to drink with, these last six months.~
@7    = ~I don't even know where to start. You know that big crater in Waukeen's Promenade? That was caused during a battle with the mage who imprisoned me.~
@8    = ~It's good to sit beside the fire with travel companions again, but you've been through a lot, I hear. Anything you want to talk about?~ [bgav103]
@9    = ~Not really, no.~
@10   = ~They captured Imoen, my oldest friend. They took her to a prison for magical deviants, and I don't even know where it is.~
@11   = ~Dynaheir and Khalid, two former friends and travel companions, are dead. Dynaheir might have died during my capture, but Khalid was flayed alive.~
@12   = ~I'm on a quest to save the world, and I don't even have a soul.~
@13   = ~And I thought I had it bad. All that happened to me was that I got lost in the Cloud Peaks and came down with a rash when a leaf I thought was goat thistle turned out not to be.~
@14   = ~How did you manage to get lost in the Cloud Peaks? That's practically your back garden, and we must have crossed through that area half a dozen times, during our travels.~
@15   = ~You're from Beregost, aren't you? That's practically your back garden. Is your sense of direction really that bad?~
@16   = ~For a cleric, your herb-lore is sadly lacking.~
@17   = ~I'm surprised at you, Gavin. Your herb-lore is better than that.~
@18   = ~I guess you haven't heard what happened to Dynaheir and Khalid, two former friends and travel companions, have you?~
@19   = ~I guess you haven't heard what happened to Dynaheir and Khalid, have you?~
@20   = ~Is that when you lost your gear? You aren't really equipped to be traveling alone.~
@21   = ~Dare I ask what happened to your gear?~
@22   = ~It gets worse. Cowled Wizards captured Imoen, my oldest friend.~
@23   = ~It gets worse. Cowled Wizards captured Imoen.~
@24   = ~My soul is gone, Gavin.~
@25   = ~Well, you've heard about the worst of it.~
@26   = ~You always were a survivor.~
@27   = ~I didn't quite tell you everything.~
@28   = ~Something to carve on my tombstone, that.~
@29   = ~If that's another way of saying 'too stubborn to die,' I suppose it's true enough.~
@30   = ~Maybe, but I'm exhausted. What say you we pick up this conversation tomorrow?~
@31   = ~I've heard that you're a survivor.~
@32   = ~That's grim news indeed. I meant to ask why she wasn't with us... I hoped the reason was that she was meeting up with us later.~
@33   = ~That's grim news indeed.~
@34   = ~What are you doing to get her back?~
@35   = ~A man named Gaelan Bayle says that he can help us, for a mere twenty thousand gold.~
@36   = ~I've made a deal with the Shadow Thieves. They will get us passage to Spellhold once I've done a few tasks for them.~
@37   = ~A... woman... named Bodhi has agreed to secure us passage to Spellhold, if we help her and her allies.~
@38   = ~I suppose I have to, don't I? I almost hate to say it, but I haven't been sorry not to have her underfoot all the time.~
@39   = ~Honestly, I have no intention of 'getting her back.' She was always a nuisance. I'm more interested in settling a debt with the bastard who tortured me.~
@40   = ~I'm sorry to hear that.~
@41   = ~The world will be a darker place without those two in it.~
@42   = ~Jaheira is taking it hard...~
@43   = ~I'll miss Dynaheir more than you know.~
@44   = ~Raise your cup, and we'll drink to their memory.~
@45   = ~I only hope they are the last companions I'll lose.~
@46   = ~It is never easy to lose those close to you.~
@47   = ~Jaheira, his widow, is taking it hard...~
@48   = ~You haven't got a soul? Helm's beard, <PRO_MANWOMAN>, I didn't know that you could live without one! How did this happen?~
@49   = ~I'm not really sure.~
@50   = ~It's all pretty complicated. I don't know if I can describe it.~
@51   = ~Irenicus extracted it like juice from grapes.~
@52   = ~I don't want to talk about it.~
@53   = ~I've got a flask right here. I'll pour, you talk.~
@54   = ~I'd as soon just drink, Gavin. A lot has happened, but I'd rather not have to relive it in the telling.~
@55   = ~Well, you know I was captured. After that, I was tortured and imprisoned. I only got free recently.~
@56   = ~They've got Imoen, Gavin. They accused her of using magic illegally and dragged her off to a prison for magical deviants.~
@57   = ~Khalid and Dynaheir are dead - killed by the mage who imprisoned me.~
@58   = ~It sounds strange saying this, but they took my soul. Literally.~
@59   = ~What's to say? You know me. I lived.~
@60   = ~He sounds powerful... and dangerous.~
@61   = ~And cruel, as well. I was tortured before I managed to escape.~
@62   = ~He said I had power, Gavin.~
@63   = ~I get chills thinking about it. Can we talk about something else?~
@64   = ~I wasn't in my right mind, at the time.~
@65   = ~It was getting on in the year, and I was still a good day out from Nashkel. We'd had a frost, and I was feeling a bit ill, since I had been going too often without enough sleep or food, so I decided to supplement my trail rations with what greens I could find. The frost had withered the leaves a bit, and I thought I was eating goat thistle.~
@66   = ~At first, I felt only a little disoriented, like I stood up too fast or had too much ale the night before, but before long, the light of my torch was leaving trails in my vision. A little while after that, I stopped being able to recognize landmarks, or even stay on the road.~
@67   = ~The next thing I knew, I was lying in a gully in a pool of mud and worse, with a nasty rash and no clear recollection of time.~
@68   = ~I still had my pack, and what little gold I had, so that was something, but I reckon I must have lost at least one day, possibly two. It took me another day to get over the after-effects of whatever it was, but by that time, I had regained my bearings, and I discovered that I had traveled a full day in the direction opposite the one I wanted.~
@69   = ~I probably have you to thank for my life. If you had not been so thorough in getting rid of the hobgoblins in the Cloud Peaks, the crows would have been picking over whatever the hobgoblins hadn't eaten.~
@70   = ~I can guess from the way you said that. I'm sorry.~
@71   = ~I sold most of what I had. I had to pay for Lanie's education, and it was far more expensive than I had planned. I don't regret the cost! No, it is what it is, and I'm glad to pay it, if it means that she learns to control her talent, but I did have to sell a few things.~
@72   = ~Besides, they say that a man who can't part with possessions in a time of need is in shackles.~
@73   = ~What else did you want to talk about?~
@74   = ~Dynaheir and Khalid, two former friends and travel companions, were killed by the mage who captured me.~
@75   = ~Dynaheir and Khalid were killed by the mage who captured me.~
@76   = ~Was that really all the gear you started with? You aren't really equipped to be traveling alone.~
@77   = ~Cowled Wizards captured Imoen, my oldest friend. 'Illegal use of magical energy,' they said.~
@78   = ~Cowled Wizards captured Imoen. 'Illegal use of magical energy,' they said.~
@79   = ~What more is there to say?~
@80   = ~Let's save that for your old age.~
@81   = ~That's good to know.~
@82   = ~There's something else I wanted to talk about before we turn in.~
@83   = ~Is that all? Still, any price is worth it, don't you think?~
@84   = ~This is Imoen we're talking about here. You know that she and I were never close. But you're right. I couldn't bring myself to abandon her.~
@85   = ~It isn't that I begrudge the gold. It's more that I don't like dealing with someone whose connections are so unsavory.~
@86   = ~I'd pay many times that, and gladly, if only I had it.~
@87   = ~Shadow Thieves! I guess it can't be helped, though, if you're to have any hope of getting Imoen back.~
@88   = ~Why did you hesitate before saying the word 'woman'?~
@89   = ~She's a vampire. I know how Lathandrites feel about undead.~
@90   = ~She's a vampire. You know what Lathander teaches us about undead.~
@91   = ~She transcends the word. I've never met anyone like her.~
@92   = ~You're imagining things.~
@93   = ~Ahem... well, at least you aren't going to leave her there.~
@94   = ~Surely you don't intend to just leave her there? I haven't been in Athkatla long at all, but I've heard what happens to those they send to their magical prison.~
@95   = ~It's only natural. Grief manifests itself in strange ways.~
@96   = ~Then I am doubly sorry for your loss.~
@97   = ~For the fallen: may the gods give them peace.~
@98   = ~As do I.~
@99   = ~Anything that can be lost can be found. We'll get it back.~
@100  = ~That's understandable. Have a glass with me, and we'll watch the fire a while... but there is one more thing I'd like to talk about before we turn in.~
@101  = ~And that was power he wanted to tap, though perhaps you'd prefer not to talk about that now. Thank the gods you escaped.~
@102  = ~Anything else, or was that all you wanted to say?~
@103  = ~Oh, there's more, all right.~
@104  = ~We're getting toward the end of it.~
@105  = ~That's it, for now.~
@106  = ~If you say so...~
@107  = ~Lathander teaches us that goodness can be found within even the most unlikely heart... though perhaps this isn't the best time for that particular sermon. In any case, you have to take whatever help you can get.~
@108  = ~Larger fortunes have been won in the City of Coin. We'll find a way to raise the money.~
@109  = ~You're right about that, but the stakes are a woman's life. I pray that Lathander will forgive the sin of allowing undead to un-live, but it would be well to make sure Imoen is safe before rectifying that.~
@110  = ~Are you saying that you'll help?~
@111  = ~I expected more opposition than that.~
@112  = ~Thanks for understanding. I did not have many options.~
@113  = ~There was no other way.~
@114  = ~We all do what we must. I'll help however I can.~
@115  = ~I feel a chill at the way you say that, but it must be my imagination. She's willing to help, so there must be some good in her.~
@116  = ~Er... yes, of course.~
@117  = ~Maybe deep down.~
@118  = ~They do say you are what you eat.~
@119  = ~I don't know and I don't care. She's agreed to help us, and that's good enough for me.~
@120  = ~I doubt it.~
@121  = ~What is that supposed to mean?~
@122  = ~Nothing, Gavin, nothing at all.~
@123  = ~Er... there's a certain agelessness about her. She must have a very good diet.~
@124  = ~She's a vampire, Gavin. I didn't want to tell you, knowing how you feel about undead, but you're bound to find out, sooner or later.~
@125  = ~Where do we go from here?~ [bgav104]
@126  = ~We take one day at a time.~
@127  = ~We go to bed and think about it tomorrow.~
@128  = ~We go on as we did before.~
@129  = ~You were gone a long time, Gavin. Much has changed.~
@130  = ~I don't know, Gavin. I haven't forgiven you yet.~
@131  = ~We make passionate love until the sun comes up and face whatever tomorrow brings together.~
@132  = ~I'd understand if you were a bit vexed with me. I was gone much longer than I told you I would be.~
@133  = ~I was a bit annoyed when weeks turned into months, but there's amusement enough to be found in Baldur's Gate. No harm done.~
@134  = ~You had a good excuse. Even if I was angry with you for not returning when you said you would, I forgave you the moment you told me what kept you.~
@135  = ~I didn't even notice.~
@136  = ~I'm angry, yes, but it will pass.~
@137  = ~You're on your last chance, Gavin. Just so you know.~
@138  = ~That's a relief.~
@139  = ~Thank you for telling me. I'll do my best not to make things worse.~
@140  = ~Well, it's getting late, and it has been a very long day. Everything always looks better in the morning.~
@141  = ~I never meant to leave you that long, you know... in Baldur's Gate, that is.~
@142  = ~I don't remember you being all that fond of me, at the time.~
@143  = ~I know. I understood that you would have come back if you could.~
@144  = ~If I was annoyed with you, I forgave you as soon as I found out the reason for your absence.~
@145  = ~I was angry with you for a long time.~
@146  = ~And now you're back. I haven't forgiven you, you know.~
@147  = ~Forget the past, Gavin. You're here now, and that's enough.~
@148  = ~Much has changed, since then. I've learned some things in the time we were apart.~
@149  = ~Enough to make you forgive me for having Bhaal for a father?~
@150  = ~Maybe you've just noticed the lack of competition you've got now.~
@151  = ~You say that now, but I'm betting that in no time flat, you'll be bitching at me now just as much as you did then. You didn't think much of the way I did things.~
@152  = ~It wasn't your fault. I didn't want the attention you were paying me.~
@153  = ~Why are you talking like we were best friends? We barely knew each other.~
@154  = ~Is this your way of saying you're sorry?~
@155  = ~Just don't get any ideas. I didn't want you then, and I don't want you now.~
@156  = ~I panicked. I knew even then that you had no control over your ancestry, but it still frightened me past all reason. I'm sorry.~
@157  = ~I was too jealous and I had no right to be. I see that now, even if I didn't see it then.~
@158  = ~Maybe I was more severe with you than I needed to be.~
@159  = ~And how do you feel about attention now?~
@160  = ~Why don't you wait and see for yourself.~
@161  = ~Attention is all right.~
@162  = ~I'm not sure.~
@163  = ~Try anything and I'll tear your arm off.~
@164  = ~I don't want that kind of attention from you.~
@165  = ~Ahem. I shall keep that in mind.~
@166  = ~Let's just see how it goes.~
@167  = ~Ahem. Yes, well, we wouldn't want that, would we?~
@168  = ~Understood.~
@169  = ~Ah. Well, Perhaps we'll get to know each other better in the future.~
@170  = ~Yes.~
@171  = ~Apology accepted.~
@172  = ~Too little, too late.~
@173  = ~What, no groveling?~
@174  = ~Thank you.~
@175  = ~Heh. I'm not very good at groveling. I hope you'll settle for a sincere apology.~
@176  = ~It was bound to happen sooner or later.~
@177  = ~Ah. Thank you for letting me know.~
@178  = ~I'm sorry.~
@179  = ~What? You mean you aren't as fixated on my flaws as you were then?~
@180  = ~I'm still a heartless bitch, you know.~
@181  = ~I deserve your scorn. I was too shallow, by far.~
@182  = ~I was too hard on you. I'm not ashamed to admit I was wrong. I'm sorry.~
@183  = ~Whatever else, your anger is justified.~
@184  = ~It's kind of you to say that, but I know that I was wrong.~
@185  = ~Yes, I suppose we do, at that.~
@186  = ~Yes, I suppose we must. Odd, how the prospect of another day can bring so little joy.~
@187  = ~That's a given, but what about *us*? I never intended to be gone so long, but I was, and I fear much may have changed since then.~
@188  = ~Nothing has changed, Gavin. I love you just as much as ever.~
@189  = ~I was angry, I admit, but I've long since forgiven you. I'm just happy you're here now.~
@190  = ~I still care about you, Gavin, but I think we may have rushed things a little too much.~
@191  = ~I saw so little of the world when I made you that promise. Now that I've seen more, I'd like a chance to experience some of the things I might have missed.~
@192  = ~There's no use in trying to phrase this delicately, so I'm not even going to try. I like making love to you, and I don't want that to end, but I just don't want the commitment. I want to experience life, and all it has to offer.~
@193  = ~I'm sorry to have to tell you this, but I've given my heart to another. I still value your company, but I've given my affection elsewhere.~
@194  = ~I can't believe you're even talking about an 'us' after everything you put me through. It's over, Gavin. Please don't make this harder than it already is.~
@195  = ~Stop fretting over the past and come to bed.~
@196  = ~I can't tell you how happy I am that you're so forgiving. Gods know I deserve a lashing or worse, for all I put you through, but here you are, just as wonderful as always.~
@197  = ~I... I see. I suppose on some level I knew that I might return to find that your feelings toward me had changed, but I had hoped that you would be able to forgive me.~
@198  = ~It has nothing to do with you, Gavin. I've never been angry with you, but can you blame me if I want to see what else is out there?~
@199  = ~It irritates me no end that you're forever putting Lanie's needs and wellbeing ahead of mine. If you hadn't been chasing her all over Faerun, we wouldn't be having this conversation now.~
@200  = ~I admit, I am a bit annoyed that you took so long getting to me, but that isn't the reason I want more freedom now. I have choices now that I didn't have then and I want to see where they lead.~
@201  = ~That is so like you, always imagining that you can charm your way out of any trouble you find yourself in. Not this time.~
@202  = ~I *do* forgive you. I understand completely why you were gone so long. It's just that, like it or not, feelings change.~
@203  = ~So... what now?~
@204  = ~Let's take a step back. I'd like our relationship to be like it was before we became engaged.~
@205  = ~I admit, I enjoy making love to you, so I don't want that to change, but I want the freedom to explore possibilities with others.~
@206  = ~We end it. I'm sorry, Gavin, I know this isn't what you want to hear, but it's the only way.~
@207  = ~You take your miserable, excuse-making ass somewhere I don't have to look at it for a while. After that, I don't even want you looking in my direction.~
@208  = ~Oh, who am I fooling? I could never leave you, even if I wanted to. Let's pretend this conversation never happened.~
@209  = ~You mean I have to try to win you all over again?~
@210  = ~You did it once.~
@211  = ~I wouldn't have put it like that, but yes, you do.~
@212  = ~If it makes you feel any better, I already like you.~
@213  = ~Ew, no. I'm not some doll at a carnival you can win by putting three darts in a bullseye.~
@214  = ~Come on, Gavin, it will be fun! You know the best part of any romance is the courtship.~
@215  = ~(sigh) I guess it could have been worse.~
@216  = ~(sigh) Wonderful. Still, it could have been worse... I guess.~
@217  = ~What? No! I never thought you were!~
@218  = ~Listen, <CHARNAME>, I'm tired. I'm saying stupid things, and when I try to fix it, I'm just making it worse.~
@219  = ~You want to go back to the way things were before we got engaged, I can do that, but I'd better stop talking now before I get myself in any more trouble.~
@220  = ~Oh, that's just wonderful. I remember the stammer and the quivering gut I had the first time around. This time should be so much better, now that I know I've already failed once.~
@221  = ~I'm sorry. I know I should be overjoyed you aren't just throwing me out on my ear. We can go back to the way things were before we got engaged.~
@222  = ~Meaning you want to sleep with me and with any other man who catches your fancy.~
@223  = ~I wasn't going to be that blunt, but yes, that's what I want.~
@224  = ~Maybe not just men, Gavin.~
@225  = ~I never said I wanted to lie with other men, Gavin. I just said I wanted the freedom to explore other possibilities.~
@226  = ~Is that so horrible?~
@227  = ~It's going to mean some changes, you know. If you do this, there is no going back. I'd never be able to trust you again.~
@228  = ~I'd always be on my guard, with you. If you drive me away, or even send me from your side, that would be it. Even if I decided to travel with you again later, I'd certainly never agree to lie with you again.~
@229  = ~Is this what you want?~
@230  = ~Yes, Gavin, it is.~
@231  = ~That's a little unreasonable, don't you think?~
@232  = ~Freedom is worth a few sacrifices. I accept your terms.~
@233  = ~Now that I think about it more, maybe it would mean giving up too much. I like the security of our relationship, and I wouldn't want that to change.~
@234  = ~No, that isn't what I want at all. Maybe we could just go back to the way we were before we became engaged.~
@235  = ~On second thought, maybe it would be better if we just ended this. Better to part on good terms than poison our friendship.~
@236  = ~What in the nine hells is wrong with you? You come back from gods know where and then make demands of me? To hells with this relationship, and to hells with you!~
@237  = ~No, I don't think it's unreasonable at all. What you're asking goes against my very nature. If I'm going to agree to it, there are going to be some changes.~
@238  = ~Oh, all right, I agree. If I get rid of you for any reason, I won't expect you to let me back into your life.~
@239  = ~Maybe we could just go back to the way we were before we became engaged.~
@240  = ~All right, I'm done. To hells with this relationship, and to hells with you!~
@241  = ~Not what I wanted to hear, but you're right. It is better than destroying our friendship.~
@242  = ~Fine! Good night.~
@243  = ~That's a relief. For a moment, there, I thought I'd lost you.~
@244  = ~Gender isn't the issue.~
@245  = ~You can't say something like that and exect me to believe you'll stop at a hug or a meaningful glance.~
@246  = ~It goes against everything I believe a loving relationship ought to be.~
@247  = ~Not what I wanted to hear, but I guess I couldn't really have expected you to forgive... not after all that time.~
@248  = ~I expected you to be angry, but this...~
@249  = ~Are you really that selfish, <CHARNAME>? If you think I could ever abandon my child for any reason, maybe you aren't the woman I thought you were.~
@250  = ~Good night.~
@251  = ~'All it has to offer'?~
@252  = ~I... I see. Well, that certainly is not something I expected to hear. Congratulations, I guess.~
@253  = ~I see. I was afraid you would feel that way, but I had to try.~
@254  = ~With you?~
@255  = ~Who else did you have in mind?~
@256  = ~Yes, with you!~
@257  = ~There's never been anyone else.~
@258  = ~I know, we've never done this before, but I think it's time we spent the night together as lovers.~
@259  = ~I don't know, Gavin. I'm not sure I'm ready.~
@260  = ~We're waiting until we're married, remember?~
@261  = ~No one but you, now and always.~
@262  = ~(Gavin folds you in his arms and eases you onto the bedroll. Tender kisses become more urgent, and the night sounds fade away.)~
@263  = ~Yes, love, I think it is.~
@264  = ~Then we'll wait until you are. It's more than enough to have you here beside me again.~
@265  = ~Good night, love. I'll see you in the morning.~
@266  = ~I remember, and I can wait. It's more than enough to be by your side once more.~
@267  = ~Well, love, the time has come for bed, and only one question remains.~
@268  = ~Where do I sleep?~
@269  = ~With me, silly!~
@270  = ~We sleep together. There's never been anyone else.~
@271  = ~Well, I know, we've never done this before, but I think it's time we spent the night together as lovers.~
@272  = ~I don't know, Gavin. I'm not sure I'm ready to sleep with you.~
@273  = ~You've always slept alone. We're waiting until we're married, remember?~
@274  = ~Aye, one day at a time, but we've both been through much since the last time we... traveled together. It changes a person.~
@275  = ~That it does, and it's odd how you sometimes only appreciate what you've lost after it's gone.~
@276  = ~If you're trying to tell me that you want to be with me again, you can forget it.~
@277  = ~I'm looking at some things in a whole new light, that's for sure.~
@278  = ~I know. Sometimes, I miss what we used to share.~
@279  = ~Some things never change. I don't regret any of the decisions I made.~
@280  = ~I've learned to appreciate my freedom more.~
@281  = ~I haven't changed a bit.~
@282  = ~I've been thinking along those lines, too. Do you think that we might want to give things another try? Together, that is?~
@283  = ~Are you going to propose to me again?~
@284  = ~Can we really do that? Go back to the way things were between us?~
@285  = ~I don't want to rush it. I've only recently started thinking of you as anything other than a nuisance. Can we take it slow?~
@286  = ~We haven't been together in quite a while, Gavin. I'd rather not get too close too fast and wind up smothering each other.~
@287  = ~I'm sorry, Gavin. It's true that I've learned to appreciate affection more, but it's because there's someone else.~
@288  = ~I can't, Gavin. I don't want to hurt you again.~
@289  = ~Oh, any love we may have shared is long since over, but I do miss the passion. I would definitely bed you again.~
@290  = ~Someday, I hope, but it's going to take time to heal the old wounds.~
@291  = ~I feel the same way.~
@292  = ~I see.~
@293  = ~(chokes) Did I just hear what I thought I heard?~
@294  = ~Are you actually saying that you would consider renewing our engagement just so I would lie with you again?~
@295  = ~Get over yourself, Gavin. There are plenty of men who can do what you did, only better. I just don't have any at hand right now.~
@296  = ~I'm considering it, yes.~
@297  = ~No, Gavin. It's over, and I know it.~
@298  = ~Not really. I value my independence too much for that. If only it were possible to have you *and* see what else life has to offer.~
@299  = ~No, there are other reasons, too. But making love to you was always special.~
@300  = ~I wouldn't let you near me with someone else's pike.~
@301  = ~I miss the passion, Gavin. I don't want to be tied down now any more than I did then, but yes, I would like to lie with you again.~
@302  = ~That's heartless, <CHARNAME>. Whatever else might have happened, you certainly are not the woman I remember.~
@303  = ~I don't know if it's wise to rush back into a commitment right away, but maybe...~
@304  = ~By that, you mean that you want to be able to sleep with me or any other man you choose?~
@305  = ~It's going to mean some changes, you know. If you do this, there is no going back. We aren't together now, but there was always the understanding that if we wanted to, we could renew our love. That chance would die. I'd never be able to trust you again.~
@306  = ~Now that I think about it more, maybe we could recover what we lost... all of it, even the love we shared.~
@307  = ~So be it.~
@308  = ~I'm sorry. I know I should be overjoyed that you're taking me back at all. We can go back to the way things were before we got engaged.~
@309  = ~Maybe if we take things slow, get used to the idea of being around each other again, it will work out better this time.~
@310  = ~I think it will. I hope it will. Let's sleep on it, and see what tomorrow brings.~
@311  = ~You were always free. I never tried to hold you back.~
@312  = ~I've learned that I can live without any man. I like it like that.~
@313  = ~You got jealous any time I even looked at another man. I could never live like that.~
@314  = ~Gavin, I loved the passion we shared. I miss it acutely, and want it back. I'm just having a hard time accepting the commitment that goes along with it.~
@315  = ~Maybe it is time to give it another try. All right, you win.~
@316  = ~You really are too good to be true! I'm months late, and not only do you forgive me, but you're ready to cover me with affection.~
@317  = ~I am the luckiest man alive!~
@318  = ~How could I ever be angry with you, love?~
@319  = ~I was angry, true, but I forgave you the moment I found out why you were so late.~
@320  = ~(joking) I'll make you pay later.~
@321  = ~Who said I've forgiven you?~
@322  = ~I wasn't going to admit it, but I wanted one more night of lovemaking to help me decide whether or not to end it.~
@323  = ~Oh, sweet, beloved <CHARNAME>, how I've longed to hold you again!~
@324  = ~Easy, Gavin! I never said I wanted to break it off immediately. Let's just sleep on it, all right?~
@325  = ~Your absence strained my affection for you, yes, but I've also become aware of possibilities that I didn't even know existed before.~
@326  = ~I'm sorry Gavin, but you were gone for a very long time, and I did lose faith. I lost faith in you and I lost faith in us.~
@327  = ~Alright...~
@328  = ~So where do I sleep?~
@329  = ~With me.~
@330  = ~Maybe it would be better if we spent the night apart, after all.~
@331  = ~Goodnight, love. Lathander bless this new beginning, it needs all the help it can get.~
@332  = ~Did you ever find out why you were abducted?~ [bgav105]
@333  = ~I can only assume it's because I'm the child of Bhaal.~
@334  = ~Maybe he just didn't like the look of me.~
@335  = ~No, and I'm not sure I want to know.~
@336  = ~He said I had potential.~
@337  = ~Why do you think?~
@338  = ~I found out, all right. He was trying to break me and rob me of my soul.~
@339  = ~Not to my satisfaction, no, but I'm on his trail. All that remains is to follow it.~
@340  = ~That isn't important. What is important is that I find him and take back what is mine.~
@341  = ~You're probably right. Do you think Irenicus will come after you again, now that you've escaped?~
@342  = ~Anything is possible, I suppose.  I hadn't wanted to think about that.~
@343  = ~The Cowled Wizards took him away as well... though now that I think about it, he went willingly, which was kind of odd.~
@344  = ~You'll protect me if he does, won't you?~
@345  = ~If he does, I'm sure I can take him.~
@346  = ~He captured me last time because I was unprepared. If he comes again, I'll be ready.~
@347  = ~I'm certain of it.~
@348  = ~Gavin, have some mercy. I'm lucky I escaped with my life. I don't want to talk about it any more.~
@349  = ~You are?! I mean... I'm sorry. That did sound a bit panicked. I don't know what I was expecting you to say, but it wasn't that.~
@350  = ~My brother Sarevok got the glowing eyes. I just got a long line of people who want to kill me.~
@351  = ~I suppose this is going to provoke a long discussion about what I am doing to overcome the evil in my blood.~
@352  = ~It isn't something I tell many people.~
@353  = ~Does this change anything?~
@354  = ~It's true, Gavin, you're in the presence of a demigod. Aren't you awed?~
@355  = ~You sound so unconcerned about it. In your place, I'd be in fear for my life.~
@356  = ~I haven't wanted to think about it.~
@357  = ~The Cowled Wizards took the mage who did it... though he went willingly, which was kind of odd.~
@358  = ~Why should I worry when I have you to protect me?~
@359  = ~I'm not worried because I know I can take care of myself.~
@360  = ~I was taken captive last time because I was unprepared. Now, I'm ready.~
@361  = ~You do, I'm sure, but the question is, what kind of potential?~
@362  = ~I have talents of all kinds, Gavin. Maybe we can try some of them out later.~
@363  = ~I have talents of all kinds, Gavin. I'm sure you remember what some of them are.~
@364  = ~I have talents of all kinds, Gavin. Maybe someday I'll show you some of my more special ones.~
@365  = ~I have many talents. For all I know, he's talking about my prowess in bed.~
@366  = ~I'm the child of Bhaal, Gavin. That probably has something to do with it.~
@367  = ~I don't know, and I'm not sure I want to find out.~
@368  = ~I only wish I knew. The things I could do with that kind of power!~
@369  = ~Of course you don't. Sorry I reminded you.~
@370  = ~I don't know what to think.~
@371  = ~Well, that comes as no surprise.~
@372  = ~That makes two of us. I don't know, and I'm not sure I want to find out.~
@373  = ~It probably has something to do with my ancestry. I'm the child of Bhaal.~
@374  = ~I don't know. Maybe he just decided that he liked my company.~
@375  = ~I imagine not, but that isn't going to make your troubles go away.~
@376  = ~I'll manage. I always do.~
@377  = ~It's probably too much to hope that my problems will go away on their own.~
@378  = ~I've always been spontaneous. I'll think of something.~
@379  = ~You sound like Gorion, my old mentor, warming up for another lecture.~
@380  = ~So what do you advise?~
@381  = ~No, love, after everything you've been through, I imagine this is the last thing you want to think about, but avoiding it isn't going to make your problems go away.~
@382  = ~That is odd. What do you make of it?~
@383  = ~Maybe he thought it would be easier to escape when less people were watching him. It did happen right in the middle of Waukeen's Promenade.~
@384  = ~He must have known he was beaten. He was casting spell after spell. He may have run out.~
@385  = ~I try not to think too hard about things like that.~
@386  = ~It's worrying, but I don't know what to make of it.~
@387  = ~Good. That's probably the best you can do, under the circumstances.~
@388  = ~Heh. Glowing eyes wouldn't be so bad, compared to having people that want to kill you. But that brings us back to our original question. What do you plan to do about it?~
@389  = ~I am concerned, I admit, but at the moment, I was thinking more of our current problem. What are you going to do if the mage who captured you comes looking for you?~
@390  = ~I'll protect you any way I can, but I'm only human. The world is full of things that are more powerful than I am... even with the blessings the Morninglord bestowed on me.~
@391  = ~Ah, there is something else I'm good for, it seems.~
@392  = ~I know you're competent, and powerful, too, but there are things in this world stronger than the both of us.~
@393  = ~You always do, but still...~
@394  = ~Well, there goes my concentration while I think about that for a while! But somehow I doubt your former captor will be interested in the talents that's making it so difficult for me to think clearly right now.~
@395  = ~(gulp) There goes my concentration for the next little while. But somehow I doubt your former captor will be distracted so easily.~
@396  = ~Ahem. Well, there's a place my brain did not need to go.~
@397  = ~You might not have a choice.~
@398  = ~Power corrupts. Absolute power corrupts absolutely. Be careful what you wish for. Those sayings might be trite, but that does not make them untrue.~
@399  = ~There's a chilling thought. With your unique heritage, there's no telling what you could do with that kind of power.~
@400  = ~Ah, that would be the famous <CHARNAME> wit.~
@401  = ~Heh. Clever.~
@402  = ~Heh. Clever and biting. Should I be amused?~
@403  = ~Anything is possible, I suppose.~
@404  = ~I can't say I blame him.~
@405  = ~If so, he has good taste, my dear.~
@406  = ~Yes, because the whole world desires you... and they probably do.~
@407  = ~It still sounds odd, though. He could have just invited you to an evening party.~
@408  = ~That's good to know. But it makes sense. You've made it this far.~
@409  = ~You always were resourceful.~
@410  = ~You always were resourceful. That's just one of the things I love about you.~
@411  = ~Probably. They seldom do.~
@412  = ~Ah, so that was his name.~
@413  = ~You've mentioned him before.~
@414  = ~Whatever his faults may have been, he did a fine job raising you.~
@415  = ~Fathers do that, I'm told. At least mine did. Still, I'm not your father, and I take the hint.~
@416  = ~If he did, it was probably because he cared about you, but I can understand how you would resent the intrusion. And I take the hint.~
@417  = ~Heh. I'm sure he thought he was doing his best to raise you properly. Still, I am not your father, and I take the hint.~
@418  = ~In that case, thank you.~
@419  = ~Nevertheless, I take it that is not a favorable comparison?~
@420  = ~He was a good man, but he did tend to preach a bit.~
@421  = ~He was a jailor as much as a foster father, always prying into my affairs.~
@422  = ~He was a tedious old windbag.~
@423  = ~It's more flattering than you think. He was a kind mentor, and I cared for him deeply.~
@424  = ~Whatever else he may be, your captor was powerful. You're no child, but you might not be a match for him yet.~
@425  = ~I'll stand by you against whatever peril comes, but even together, I don't know if we're strong enough.~
@426  = ~Even if I didn't love you so absolutely, I'd stand by you against whatever peril comes, but even together, I don't know if we're strong enough.~
@427  = ~The best advice I can give you is to do everything you can to make sure you're ready if your paths cross again. Study, train, whatever it takes. I understand your need is grave, but don't force an encounter until you're confident that you'll succeed.~
@428  = ~It's possible. Even the most powerful spellcasters exhaust their reserves, eventually. But he'll have rested since then, and the next time you face him, he might be at full strength again. Have you given much thought to what you'll do if that happens?~
@429  = ~Neither do I. I hate to bring it up, but have you given much thought to what you'll do if your paths cross again?~
@430  = ~I should imagine not. Thank you for trusting me enough to tell me.~
@431  = ~No. I'd be lying if I said your revelation didn't concern me, but you didn't incinerate me on sight, so you must have some control.~
@432  = ~My immediate concern is what you'll do if your paths cross again. Have you given it much thought?~
@433  = ~We'll see to it at once.~
@434  = ~When I left the Sword Coast behind me, I had hoped that I traveled to a more enlightened place, but instead, I find just as much prejudice here as I did in Baldur's Gate... or even more.~ [bgav106]
@435  = ~Why would you expect such a foolish thing? People are people, no matter where they live.~
@436  = ~Tell me about it. I've had more stares since I arrived here than ever I got back in Baldur's Gate.~
@437  = ~We're here because we've got a job to do, not because we're trying to convert the populace to Lathander.~
@438  = ~You've been helping me, Gavin, not spreading your faith. I'm grateful for everything you do, but we have been focused on other things.~
@439  = ~It is discouraging, isn't it?~
@440  = ~I think we are in a more enlightened place. It's better for each race to keep to its own kind.~
@441  = ~I know, but that doesn't excuse it.~
@442  = ~I can't say I'm surprised. There are even times I find myself staring at you, too, and I'm your companion...~
@443  = ~I can't say I'm surprised, and I don't think it's because you're a <PRO_RACE>. There are even times I find myself staring at you, too, and I'm your companion...~
@444  = ~I can't say I'm surprised, and I don't think it's because you're an elf. There are even times I find myself staring at you, too, and I'm your companion...~
@445  = ~That sounded much better in my head. What I mean is that you're easy to look at...~
@446  = ~Whew, this just gets better and better.~
@447  = ~I know I can't stop looking at you, and I don't ever want to try, but everyone can't share my tastes, thank goodness...~
@448  = ~That's because you're an oddity.~
@449  = ~That didn't come out right.~
@450  = ~My point is that there is something about you that almost compels people to look at you. I don't mean this in an offensive way. I just mean that you are profoundly different than most people you meet, and you and I both know why.~
@451  = ~And no, I don't think everyone who sees you knows who and what you are. It's just that maybe they can sense that there is something different about you, and they stare out of curiosity.~
@452  = ~'Who and what' I am? What is that supposed to mean?~
@453  = ~All right, but that doesn't explain why you're always looking at me.~
@454  = ~It isn't fair. I have no control over my ancestry.~
@455  = ~Not everyone sees me with your eyes, Gavin. To them, I'm nothing special.~
@456  = ~You'd think people would find other things to look at. There are far odder-looking people than me on the street.~
@457  = ~You got side-tracked again. You were talking about how you're finding Amn to be as narrow-minded as you found the Sword Coast.~
@458  = ~I... I heard a rumor. I don't usually go around listening to gossip or prying into peoples' past, so please don't think I'm being intrusive, but that kind of thing makes an impression.~
@459  = ~Don't believe everything you hear.~
@460  = ~Well, it's true. Do you hate me now?~
@461  = ~That's a despicable lie. You should be ashamed of yourself for ever believing such a thing.~
@462  = ~So you heard a rumor. And now you think that just because you believe something to be true, so does everyone else.~
@463  = ~Thank you for trusting me enough to tell me. It can't have been easy for you to do.~
@464  = ~I'm sorry. That was a terrible accusation I made against you, and I apologize.~
@465  = ~I don't know whether to believe it or not... and 'don't believe everything you hear' is not exactly a denial. But if you are the child of Bhaal, don't you think I have a right to know?~
@466  = ~I'm not.~
@467  = ~No, I don't, but it isn't because I don't value your company. This isn't the first time someone has asked. Even if I deny it, you'll think I am, anyway.~
@468  = ~I suppose you do. It's true.~
@469  = ~No.~
@470  = ~(sigh) I really hoped you weren't going to follow up on that lapse. I'm going to try to put this as delicately as I can.~
@471  = ~I'm a man. No matter how much I try to confine myself to... er... higher beliefs and ideals, I'm... oh, damn.~
@472  = ~Our friend is trying to tell you that, while he strives to conduct himself with all possible decorum, he is incapable of ignoring the attractions you hold.~
@473  = ~Have mercy, <CHARNAME>! Our fumbling friend is trying to tell you that he finds your countenance agreeable.~
@474  = ~Har, har! The lad's got a pike in his leggin's for ye, but he's too bashful to say it.~
@475  = ~Come, my hound, can you not tell her that you find her face fair to look upon?~
@476  = ~What the oaf is trying and failing to say is that he finds you comely. (Could my opinion of this baboon's eloquence, or lack thereof, sink any lower?)~
@477  = ~Friend Gavin is trying to tell you that he thinks you're pretty.~
@478  = ~Just say it, Gavin. She's a woman and you're attracted to her.~
@479  = ~Interesting. Among animals, males rarely have difficulty communicating their desires to the females. Though perhaps, in this case, there is only attraction, rather than an active desire to mate.~
@480  = ~Reminds me of the time my cousin Todo took a shine to that girl in Sweetheart Lane. Couldn't get an intelligible sentence out of him for a week.~
@481  = ~Get a grip on yourself, man. This is no time to be bothering our leader with oafish flatteries.~
@482  = ~Ilmater's mercy, I don't believe the words that come out of my mouth. Forgive me.~
@483  = ~Can we please return to what we were talking about in the first place? I said that I couldn't believe how prejudiced Amn is and you agreed.~
@484  = ~After that, there was an embarassing display of my ability to humiliate myself, and now, I'd like to go back to talking about Amn... or anything else, really.~
@485  = ~I think I'm done talking for a while.~
@486  = ~Don't worry, Gavin. I find your awkwardness endearing.~
@487  = ~Right... Amn... Prejudice. Yes, I agree. I hadn't expected to find so much of it here, either.~
@488  = ~I don't know if things are any worse here, but I didn't really expect them to be better. People are still people, even if you cross a border.~
@489  = ~Actually, I didn't agree. I'm just as happy if things are the way they are. Each race should keep to its own kind.~
@490  = ~I'm sorry my ill-considered words put an end to this discussion, but I understand your desire to keep moving.~
@491  = ~Well, that's something, at least. I keep hoping that one day, I'll grow out of it, but it hasn't happened yet.~
@492  = ~Anyway...~
@493  = ~In any case, I'd be a hypocrite if I based my opinion of a person on ancestry alone, no matter how... different it might be.~
@494  = ~Oh, I know. None of us can.~
@495  = ~No doubt! And ones less...~
@496  = ~Yes, yes. But it isn't fair for people to judge based on appearances.~
@497  = ~'Ones less' what, Gavin?~
@498  = ~Yes, that's right, I was.~
@499  = ~You will always be something special, love. If others don't see that, they're blind, but I won't complain about that. If they weren't, I might have to fight another for your honor every time we went out of doors.~
@500  = ~But it is troubling that people are so quick to judge.~
@501  = ~I know, but it's hard to see so much inequity around us and feel anything but disappointment.~
@502  = ~With so much inequity around us, it's hard to feel anything but disappointment.~
@503  = ~You don't really believe that, do you?~
@504  = ~I do. Very firmly.~
@505  = ~It isn't that I have anything against <PRO_RACE> and non-<PRO_RACE> living side by side, but I fear that culture may be lost forever, should each race lose its identity.~
@506  = ~I've got nothing against your average non-<PRO_RACE>, but <PRO_RACE> and non-<PRO_RACE> should never wed.~
@507  = ~No, I probably spoke too hastily. I'm not really that biased.~
@508  = ~I'm sorry you feel that way. I pray that one day, you'll reconsider.~
@509  = ~That's a valid concern, <CHARNAME>. We all should keep the best of what we are, our faith, our culture, our art, and strive to rid ourselves of the worst, distrust, hate, war.~
@510  = ~I see. I would never tell another where he should give his heart, but it seems wrong to me that one <PRO_RACE> could only find happiness with another <PRO_RACE>. Yet in matters of love, moreso than anywhere else, each person must follow what he believes to be right.~
@511  = ~We all do that, from time to time. No harm done.~
@512  = ~A person's actions define them, not the shape of the ears or the blood in the veins.~
@513  = ~Lathander teaches us that, but damn me, I can't seem to help people understand it. There are times when I feel like such a failure for not being able to get that simple point across.~
@514  = ~Lathander also teaches us to guide, rather than compel. We can't force people to adhere to our beliefs.~
@515  = ~Would Lathander really advocate trying to force people to adhere to a set of beliefs?~
@516  = ~Maybe you just aren't persuasive enough.~
@517  = ~You have to believe in yourself. If you don't, no one else will.~
@518  = ~You can't change the world in a day, Gavin. You just need more time.~
@519  = ~Why bother? If people want to believe that they're better than everyone else, you can always laugh at them when they're proven wrong.~
@520  = ~The world is a big place, and you're just one man.~
@521  = ~Why are you worrying about this when you're supposed to be helping me with my quest?~
@522  = ~You're right. Failed again.~
@523  = ~Now there's an understatement.~
@524  = ~'Always another morning?'~
@525  = ~Heh. And I guess it starts with me, doesn't it?~
@526  = ~You're right, of course.~
@527  = ~I worry about it because it's a tenet of my faith... but you're right. I should be more worried about your quest.~
@528  = ~I try, <CHARNAME>, I try, but sometimes, it isn't easy.~
@529  = ~There are days, sometimes, when I don't think I can do anything right.~
@530  = ~You're only human, Gavin. You shouldn't expect so much from yourself.~
@531  = ~And there are days when you seem to do the impossible. It all balances out in the end.~
@532  = ~This isn't like you, Gavin. You're not usually this negative.~
@533  = ~We all have days like that. It's called life.~
@534  = ~You think you have it tough? Try having the blood of a god in your veins.~
@535  = ~You're right. Better to look at personal failings as opportunities to grow. It is tough, sometimes, though.~
@536  = ~I think I can change the world, and that's just another kind of pride. We're supposed to strive against that, you know. It's an obstacle to growth.~
@537  = ~You really know how to cheer a person up, <CHARNAME>. Thank you.~
@538  = ~It's just a mood, I guess. It will pass.~
@539  = ~I guess you're right. And I guess you know how frustrating it is, too.~
@540  = ~True. I should give thanks for my blessings.~
@541  = ~Who does?~
@542  = ~No idea, but it would have to be worse.~
@543  = ~I do.~
@544  = ~Depends on the god, I guess. If I carried the blood of Liira, goddess of dancing, maybe I wouldn't end up in a heap quite so often. But one of the others... Bhaal, for instance... no I wouldn't want that.~
@545  = ~Which one?~
@546  = ~Sune.~
@547  = ~Chauntea.~
@548  = ~Tempus.~
@549  = ~Ubtao.~
@550  = ~Gond.~
@551  = ~Tymora.~
@552  = ~Deneir.~
@553  = ~Eldath.~
@554  = ~Sharess.~
@555  = ~Bhaal.~
@556  = ~That explains your looks, then.~
@557  = ~Interesting. I was unaware that she bore any mortal offspring.~
@558  = ~That explains your... er... figure.~
@559  = ~Remind me never to get you angry.~
@560  = ~Talk about exotic. I never would have dreamed of that one.~
@561  = ~So, you're good with your hands? Er...~
@562  = ~Some people have all the luck.~
@563  = ~Now we know why you're so clever.~
@564  = ~If you inherited that placid nature, our current way of life must be a challenge for you.~
@565  = ~(gulp) You don't say.~
@566  = ~You're serious. I... I didn't know.~
@567  = ~I'm sorry. I don't mean to be rude, but this is a bit of a shock.~
@568  = ~I'm not a monster, Gavin.~
@569  = ~That's why I don't tell many people.~
@570  = ~Aren't you going to remark on how you always thought I had a violent nature?~
@571  = ~It was a shock at first, but I've grown tired of it, by now.~
@572  = ~No, I never thought you were.~
@573  = ~Perfectly understandable.~
@574  = ~If I was, it wouldn't be because of what you just told me.~
@575  = ~I guess a person can get used to anything.~
@576  = ~I'd rather base my opinion of you on your actions, rather than on your blood, but I do have to ask... does your heritage affect you in any way?~
@577  = ~Apart from a preference for rare meat, no.~
@578  = ~When I was a child, I used to collect skulls, if that counts.~
@579  = ~It's a constant battle, Gavin. I feel the rage in me, but I resist it.~
@580  = ~When people find out about it, they either want to kill me or find a way to use whatever power I inherited from my sire for their own purposes.~
@581  = ~Not at all.~
@582  = ~If you're joking about it, I would say the answer is no.~
@583  = ~I can't even imagine the strength of will you must possess to combat it.~
@584  = ~It sounds like a hard life... and I certainly understand why you're reluctant to tell many people.~
@585  = ~You're fortunate.~
@586  = ~I thank you for trusting me enough to tell me that. As long as you fight the evil in your blood, I'll help you any way that I can. And I believe you can fight it, or you wouldn't have made it this far.~
@587  = ~Interesting. I wasn't aware that he sired any mortal offspring.~
@588  = ~Still, it could be worse. Your sire could be Bhaal... and everyone knows that he has offspring living today.~
@589  = ~Are your spirits holding up all right?~
@590  = ~Your foul mood is contagious. I was fine before, but not anymore.~
@591  = ~I'm alright. Maybe a bit tired.~
@592  = ~I've been a bit moody myself, lately. One moment, I'm cheerful, the next, not so much.~
@593  = ~Nothing ever upsets me.~
@594  = ~I feel restless, like there's something I should be doing, but I don't know what it is.~
@595  = ~This isn't really something I want to talk about with you.~
@596  = ~If I told you I was unhappy, what would you do to try to cheer me up?~
@597  = ~So how about you? Are your spirits holding up all right?~
@598  = ~I'm sorry. I guess I'd better just shut up before I make it worse.~
@599  = ~I'm sorry, dear one.~
@600  = ~Sorry about that.~
