@794  = ~I am Faithless.~
@795  = ~You walk a dangerous path, <CHARNAME>! Death can come at any time, even for those who are not adventurers. Do you want to spend eternity trapped in the Wall of the Faithless?~
@796  = ~What is the Wall of the Faithless, exactly?~
@797  = ~Good point. Maybe I need to think some more about my faith.~
@798  = ~I just haven't found a god whose nature suits me.~
@799  = ~I'll take my chances.~
@800  = ~Faith is a personal thing, Gavin. You can't advise me.~
@801  = ~You have no right to tell me what I should or should not believe.~
@802  = ~When mortals die, their souls go to Kelemvor, the god of the dead, on the Fugue Plane. There, the avatars of their gods claim them and take the souls of the deceased to reside on their deities' home planes.~
@803  = ~When a mortal has no god, whether by choice or because his god has died, Kelemvor consigns his soul to the Wall of the Faithless. The souls are trapped in an unbreakable web of slime and mold.~
@804  = ~Over time, the trapped souls lose any sense of identity, and eventually, they dissolve into the wall itself and cease to be.~
@805  = ~Lemurs, lesser demons, prey upon souls trapped in the wall, stealing them away and taking them back to the Abyss to suffer eternal torment.~
@806  = ~This is the fate that awaits you, <CHARNAME>, if you die without a patron.~
@807  = ~That doesn't seem fair!~
@808  = ~So all I have to do is declare a patron and I'm saved?~
@809  = ~I guess I need to give some thought to finding a patron.~
@810  = ~Oblivion isn't so bad. It's certainly better than slavishly following the decrees of some god.~
@811  = ~Honestly, Gavin, this is none of your business.~
@812  = ~I can't tell you what to believe. All I can do is urge you to think about it. I know it seems foolish to waste time and effort pondering the merits of different faiths, but eternity is a long time to regret your decision now.~
@813  = ~Perhaps I am being intrusive, but I am only concerned about the future wellbeing of your soul. I will desist, though, since I can see this is not something you want to talk about.~
@814  = ~Fairness is a mortal concept, not a godly one. We can't even hope to understand the ways of the gods, let alone judge the equity of their decisions.~
@815  = ~Paying lip-service to the gods is not enough. Those who declare a faith but don't embrace it suffer the same fate as the Faithless.~
@816  = ~If that is your choice, so be it, but eternity is a long time to regret decisions you make now.~
@817  = ~Yes, I understand that is not unusual among elves. As a human I find the concept of choosing more than one god as a patron strange, but then, perhaps you find human customs odd, as well.~
@818  = ~No offense, <CHARNAME>, but isn't that a bit of a contradiction, based on your... er... personal values?~
@819  = ~People can change, Gavin, and a desire to better oneself is only natural. Is it wrong to aspire toward an ideal?~
@820  = ~Ironic, isn't it?~
@821  = ~My beliefs are my affair.~
@822  = ~Non-human pantheons are not as diverse as human ones. I don't have a lot of options.~
@823  = ~Since you do seek to better yourself, would you ever consider converting? Leaving selfishness and deceit behind and embracing a more benevolent outlook?~
@824  = ~I'd consider it, yes.~
@825  = ~I would need to think about it more.~
@826  = ~No, I don't think I can change that much.~
@827  = ~Not if you mean it. Since you put your faith in a benevolent deity, might you not take that as a sign that you are meant to better yourself? Leave selfishness and deceit behind and completely embrace your deity's teachings?~
@828  = ~You always have options. Since you have found your faith, could you not take that as a sign that you are meant to better yourself? Leave selfishness and deceit behind and completely embrace your deity's teachings?~
@829  = ~Well, that's good to hear!~
@830  = ~Still, I won't stop hoping. There's always another morning.~
@831  = ~That is fortunate! Our faiths are allied with each other. I hope our causes will be, too.~
@832  = ~I hope so, too.~
@833  = ~They seem to be, so far.~
@834  = ~Time will tell.~
@835  = ~There are no guarantees we will get along just because our gods are friends.~
@836  = ~That is fortunate! We share the same faith, so it's likely we'll share the same causes, too.~
@837  = ~I hope so.~
@838  = ~It seems that way, so far.~
@839  = ~There are no guarantees we will get along just because we worship the same god.~
@840  = ~It bodes well for our future.~
@841  = ~Still, I am optimistic. People who hold similar beliefs often get along quite well. It bodes well for the future.~
@842  = ~Still, I will not give up all hope. We might yet find some common ground between us.~
@843  = ~That bodes well for our future, but I have to ask. Would you ever consider finding a new patron? If you aspire to better things, would it not make sense to see if there is some other god whose nature suits you better?~
@844  = ~That would present some problems, wouldn't you say? I am a cleric, after all.~
@845  = ~I need to think about it.~
@846  = ~I've been considering that myself.~
@847  = ~No, I think not.~
@848  = ~That does present some problems, doesn't it?~
@849  = ~That would probably be a good idea. If your values have changed, it would serve you well to consider all possibilities.~
@850  = ~Our faiths, at least, are in accord. I hope our causes will be, too.~
@851  = ~There are no guarantees we will get along just because our gods are both benevolent deities.~
@852  = ~Well, at least our faiths are not at odds with each other. I hope our causes will be in accord.~
@853  = ~There are no guarantees we will get along just because our gods are not enemies.~
@854  = ~Hmm. That's unfortunate. I only hope we'll be able to get along, even if our faiths are at odds with each other.~
@855  = ~I wouldn't count on it, if I were you.~
@856  = ~I could have been asking you whether you believe in things beyond your perception. Do you?~
@857  = ~No. If I can see it and I can touch it, it's real.~
@858  = ~Emotions are intangible, but I know they exist, so yes, I guess so.~
@859  = ~It's a big world, Gavin. We can't sense all of it, but that doesn't mean it doesn't exist.~
@860  = ~Are you playing games with me?~
@861  = ~I try not to think about too many abstract ideas. It tends to slow my reflexes.~
@862  = ~If I cover this coin with my hand, does it cease to exist? You can't see it or touch it.~
@863  = ~No good. I still know it's there.~
@864  = ~I can't see it or touch it, but you can.~
@865  = ~Point taken.~
@866  = ~That's an overly simple analogy, don't you think?~
@867  = ~So, it exists because you remember it. But what of the coin in my pouch? You've never seen it. Does it exist?~
@868  = ~But that doesn't matter. I've made my point. There are a lot of things we have to take on faith, and a lot more is possible than we ever dreamed could be.~
@869  = ~So, you'll take my word for it because I can see and touch it. But what of the coin in my pouch? For all I know, it fell out days ago. Does that exist?~
@870  = ~Yes, there are a lot of things we have to take on faith. More is possible than we ever dreamed could be.~
@871  = ~Is it? It's hard to get more simple than a thing's existence, but even that is by no means certain. Consider the coin in my pouch. You've never seen it, or heard me mention it before now. Does it exist?~
@872  = ~The reality of emotion as proof of the intangible. I like that. It's a lot deeper than it seems on the surface, because emotions can be so easily misconstrued. Is it disappointment, or is it boredom? An observer might not be able to tell, but that makes it no less real.~
@873  = ~You've got more wisdom than many, to understand that.~
@874  = ~No games, <CHARNAME>, though perhaps you tire of this conversation. Let's catch up with the others, then.~
@875  = ~It also tends to deflect the question. Nevermind. I'll leave you be.~
@876  = ~I'd like to believe that, too.~
@877  = ~I'm a little surprised to hear you say it, though.~
@878  = ~I haven't had a normal life, Gavin. If things had been different, I'm sure I wouldn't have turned out the way I did.~
@879  = ~I think I *am* a good person, deep down. My actions haven't always been good, and I'm ashamed of that, but I've always intended to do the right thing.~
@880  = ~There are bound to be exceptions. I'm one.~
@881  = ~If people weren't good by nature, they wouldn't be such easy targets for the rest of us.~
@882  = ~I'm glad to hear you say that, <CHARNAME>. It gives me great hope for the future.~
@883  = ~It's never too late to change, and even the oldest wound can be persuaded to heal, with the right medicine. You just have to believe it's possible.~
@884  = ~Oh, <CHARNAME>, why must you say these things? But I can't give up hope. I must not.~
@885  = ~I'm not surprised to hear you say that, but it's good to hear, nonetheless.~
@886  = ~I had a lot of love and support while I was growing up, though. Some people didn't, and if they turned out worse, I wouldn't blame them for it.~
@887  = ~Even good people make mistakes, though. Maybe there are some that just keep making them, even though they may want to do better.~
@888  = ~There are bound to be exceptions, though. Some people are just plain bad.~
@889  = ~It's a pity, though, because it just makes us easy targets for those with less scruples.~
@890  = ~We have to keep hoping, <CHARNAME>. Even those that did not have the benefit of a loving home or who have made mistakes can be redeemed. I feel it in my soul.~
@891  = ~Do you really believe that, despite things that others have done for you, with no hope of reward? Do you really think people are evil by nature?~
@892  = ~No, not really.~
@893  = ~How disappointing. I had hoped you would not be so cynical.~
@894  = ~I've tried to be better. My actions haven't always been good, and I'm ashamed of that, but I've always intended to do the right thing.~
@895  = ~Wishing won't change a person's nature.~
@896  = ~I wouldn't mind if people were more gullible. They would be easier targets for the rest of us.~
@897  = ~So are you the lone exception?~
@898  = ~I had a lot of love and support while I was growing up, though. Most didn't, and if they turned out worse, I wouldn't blame them for it.~
@899  = ~Everyone makes mistakes. Maybe there are some that just keep making them, even if they want to do better.~
@900  = ~I wouldn't say I'm the only exception, but most people are just plain bad.~
@901  = ~It would be nice if there were more exceptions. It would make them easier targets.~
@902  = ~It's always possible, but will you humor me and answer the question? What do you believe?~
@903  = ~Maybe you're asking me about my god, or maybe about some higher power.~
@904  = ~No, Gavin, I don't want to answer.~
@905  = ~If you like.~
@906  = ~I think people are basically good.~
@907  = ~I think people are interested only in themselves.~
@908  = ~Anything else?~
@909  = ~That about covers it.~
@910  = ~Thank you for indulging my curiosity.~
@911  = ~Then I won't trouble you more about it.~
@912  = ~<CHARNAME>, I've got something I need to talk to you about, and I doubt it's going to be a comfortable conversation for either of us.~ [bgav108]
@913  = ~An ominous beginning, but go on.~
@914  = ~Then we shouldn't discuss it.~
@915  = ~Maybe another time would be better?~
@916  = ~I'm mortal, <CHARNAME>, and like all things mortal, I will die.~
@917  = ~I would rather this happen after your quest is completed, and after Lanie is grown and settled, but we can't name the hour of our death.~
@918  = ~When this happens, I need you to promise you won't try to raise me.~
@919  = ~I'll do nothing of the kind! The gods bestow the power to raise the dead for a reason.~
@920  = ~Why would you ask such a thing of me?~
@921  = ~Nothing will happen to you, if I have any say in the matter.~
@922  = ~But what of us? What of our love?~
@923  = ~I know this is important to you. I will do as you ask.~
@924  = ~I can't make you that promise.~
@925  = ~We have to discuss it. I'm sorry, but it isn't something we can ignore.~
@926  = ~There is no better time than the present. I hope it will not take long.~
@927  = ~The gods bestow the power to raise the dead for a number of reasons, but... let me explain.~
@928  = ~We who follow Lathander believe that the souls of the faithful return to Lathander. We consider it coming home to our god. We dwell with him for a time, then are returned to the mortal world in the bodies of newborns, completing the Great Cycle that begins and ends with birth.~
@929  = ~Raising interrupts that cycle, returning the soul to the world of the living without the solace of a homecoming.~
@930  = ~The only time this is condoned is if the deceased has unfinished business here on Toril.~
@931  = ~So, if you have 'unfinished business,' you could be raised?~
@932  = ~And who decides that you have left work undone?~
@933  = ~But what of our love? Isn't that reason enough to come back?~
@934  = ~I understand. I'll do as you ask.~
@935  = ~I'm sorry, Gavin. I can't make any promises. I'd like to follow your wishes, but if I still need you, I'm going to have to attempt to raise you.~
@936  = ~No. I won't agree to anything so foolish.~
@937  = ~That spares me some guilt, at least. Now I just have to find a convenient way for you to die.~
@938  = ~I'm glad you're looking out for me, but I leave all in Lathander's hands. If it's his will that I should return to him, there is no force on Toril that could prevent it, and if it is his will that I remain here, then I have nothing to worry about.~
@939  = ~And if it's his will that you be raised, you would accept that as readily?~
@940  = ~Alright, but why are you determined not to be raised?~
@941  = ~I know this is important to you, so I will do as you ask.~
@942  = ~I can't make you any promises.~
@943  = ~<CHARNAME>, beloved, please do not ask me to choose between you and my faith! Maybe I should explain.~
@944  = ~I am relieved, though I understand that if my time comes while I am with you, new questions might arise. If that happens, you'll get answers from High Mornmaster Arval at the Temple in Athkatla.~
@945  = ~All I can ask is that you consider my wishes, should I fall in your service. If that happens, you can seek the advice of High Mornmaster Arval at the Temple in Athkatla. He may be able to explain things in a way you find easier to understand.~
@946  = ~Perhaps, though if I've fallen in battle, I would be in no position to say whether I had work left to do.~
@947  = ~I would consider my death as a sign that my work on Toril was done... though I am not arrogant enough to say whether Lathander would agree or disagree.~
@948  = ~It is hard, <CHARNAME>. Since Lathander does permit resurrection, who am I to say whether death is a final reward or a test of faith?~
@949  = ~Under the circumstances, I would prefer to leave the decision in the hands of those better schooled in my faith than I. High Mornmaster Arval would be able to answer these questions that I cannot.~
@950  = ~(sigh) I would want it, though my faith itself forbade it... though perhaps I am not the one who should make that decision.~
@951  = ~<CHARNAME>... please...~
@952  = ~Ha! You always were a clever one, <CHARNAME>, and always ready with a good joke...~
@953  = ~That was a joke, wasn't it?~
@954  = ~There is one other matter, and it is more important than my continued existence on Toril.~
@955  = ~Lanie resides at the Temple of Oghma in the Docks. Should I fall, please tell the priest of Oghma. He will break the news to Lanie, and notify my family in Ulgoth's Beard and Mornmaster Ormlyr at the Song of the Morning.~
@956  = ~What will happen to Lanie if you die?~
@957  = ~If you die, I'll tell him.~
@958  = ~We'll see.~
@959  = ~If I even remember.~
@960  = ~She will finish her studies and then she will go to my brother Gordon in Ulgoth's Beard. He has a family of his own, and I know that he and his wife will love Lanie as if she were their daughter.~
@961  = ~Thank you for agreeing to do this for me.~
@962  = ~Please, <CHARNAME>, this is no time for jest, assuming it is a jest. This is a child's life we're talking about.~
@963  = ~Please... you're in Athkatla all the time. It isn't too much to ask.~
@964  = ~<CHARNAME>, have you ever seen something you've wanted to forget, but couldn't?~ [bgav109]
@965  = ~Yes, that time you decided to sluice off in that stream. Some things are better left unseen.~
@966  = ~How can you even ask that, knowing what I've been through?~
@967  = ~I'll worry more when I can see horrors and forget them.~
@968  = ~Not really. Bad things happen, even monstrous things. It doesn't do you any good to dwell on them.~
@969  = ~Would it help to talk about it?~
@970  = ~Here we go again. Gavin cries tears of blood for some fool too stupid to stay out of trouble. You should have been a priest of Ilmater.~
@971  = ~Heh. I didn't realize anyone could see me. Sorry about that.~
@972  = ~Ilmater's blood, I didn't realize anyone could see me. I'm sorry.~
@973  = ~Don't apologize. I liked what I saw. It's just that the memory is rather distracting.~
@974  = ~Don't apologize. I liked what I saw. It's just that with the way things are between us...~
@975  = ~Next time, you might want to look around before you take your clothes off.~
@976  = ~It isn't fair to show me things like that when I'm supposed to have my mind on someone else.~
@977  = ~So how did you get that scar on your back?~
@978  = ~There's something about you that I find repellent.~
@979  = ~No offense. I prefer women.~
@980  = ~You did? I mean... er... yes, but it's the principle of the thing...~
@981  = ~Ahem.~
@982  = ~Nothing is broken beyond all mending, but we can talk about that later, if you like.~
@983  = ~Yes, some things are broken beyond all mending.~
@984  = ~I thought I did.~
@985  = ~Er... yes.~
@986  = ~When we were boys, Calahan and my brother were pretending to be Hurgan Stoneblade and throwing axes. Calahan missed.~
@987  = ~Good to know... I guess.~
@988  = ~Oh, no. Do you... did you find the sight repulsive?~
@989  = ~Not at all! It's just that seeing you that way has made it a bit hard for me to think about other things, like my quest.~
@990  = ~It does make me wonder what you'd look like if the water weren't so cold.~
@991  = ~No, it's just that I thought we were saving that until after we're married. Now you've gone and spoiled the surprise.~
@992  = ~Let's just say that when the time comes, we'll be blowing out all the lamps.~
@993  = ~And we can't be having that, now, can we, love?~
@994  = ~Much different. Much, much different. Ahem.~
@995  = ~Oh, love, I'm sorry. Honestly, I didn't realize you could see me.~
@996  = ~Wonderful.~
@997  = ~Beshaba's breath. There's only one thing I've got that you'll accept, and you can't stand the sight of me?~
@998  = ~I thought you'd be more manly. Your chest is as hairless as a babe's.~
@999  = ~In the dark, all cats are gray.~
@1000 = ~Just give the word when you want me to come to you, then.~
@1001 = ~I spend years of my life making sure my body is fit and strong, and she complains because I haven't got a pelt.~
@1002 = ~Ilmater's blood, I thought...~
@1003 = ~Oh, no! I enjoyed the view. It's just that seeing you that way has made it a bit hard for me to think about other things, like my quest.~
@1004 = ~(giggle) Don't worry. I know it was just the cold water.~
@1005 = ~If I saw you, anybody else could have, too. I thought that you only showed off for me.~
@1006 = ~There's a good reason I like it better when the lamps are out.~
@1007 = ~Is that so? Maybe we'll have to do something about that later, yes?~
@1008 = ~That's right... cold water.~
@1009 = ~I do... well, not showing off, exactly...~
@1010 = ~<CHARNAME>, love, I was filthy. I really needed a bath. There was really nothing more to it than that.~
@1011 = ~You've never complained before.~
@1012 = ~I'm not complaining now! It's just that seeing you that way has made it a bit hard for me to think about other things, like my quest.~
@1013 = ~Usually, the only time I see you naked is before you come to bed. Seeing you out in the open like that, all pale and hairless, well...~
@1014 = ~If you want me to come to you when you retire, say so, and I'll be there.~
@1015 = ~I... I'm sorry. After everything you've been through, for me to make such a stupid remark... I'm sorry.~
@1016 = ~And you have, too.~
@1017 = ~But sometimes, you can't help it... but you've seen worse than I. And I'm an idiot.~
@1018 = ~When I left your company, not long after we met, Lanie and I went to the Temple of Oghma. On the way, I saw a group of ruffians assaulting a prostitute, laughing while they beat her. She was crying, begging for help, and no one paid her any heed.~
@1019 = ~I did nothing to help her. I just picked Lanie up and carried her past, hiding her face so she wouldn't see what was happening. But she had to have heard it.~
@1020 = ~When we finally got to the temple and I put her down, she just looked at me, silent and grave. 'You saw and you did nothing,' her eyes said to me, and I had no answer.~
@1021 = ~I don't know what haunts me more, the viciousness of the attack, the indifference of the passers-by, or the accusation in my child's eyes.~
@1022 = ~What could you have done? You couldn't have left Lanie alone to help the girl. Someone would have stolen her away.~
@1023 = ~You made a mistake. You should have gone back once you saw that Lanie was safe.~
@1024 = ~You could have called the guard, at least.~
@1025 = ~What's done is done. Guilt will only drive you mad.~
@1026 = ~This is Athkatla, Gavin. People see worse every day.~
@1027 = ~What do you care what happens to some whore?~
@1028 = ~That was my fear, as well. Unattended children are not safe in Athkatla.~
@1029 = ~I tried going back to see if the woman was all right, but by the time I found a monk to watch Lanie for a moment, the fight was over. She was gone, and there was nothing but blood on the paving stones to show that any wrong had ever been done. I asked where she went, or if she was even alive, but no one would answer. No one seemed to care.~
@1030 = ~What guard? I saw none from the moment I entered the Docks.~
@1031 = ~It may, and it should. I felt helpless.~
@1032 = ~And that's the worst part. They see worse and do nothing. When I finally found a monk to watch Lanie for a moment, I went back, but the fight was over, and no one would tell me where the woman went or even if she was still alive. No one seemed to care.~
@1033 = ~Someone has to care, because it doesn't seem like anyone else will. When I finally found a monk to watch Lanie for a moment, I went back, but the fight was over, and no one would tell me where the woman went or even if she was still alive. It was like nothing had ever happened.~
@1034 = ~Are you indifferent to the suffering of others, or are you just mocking my sympathetic nature?~
@1035 = ~You get upset about things no sane person would think twice about. You have to toughen up, Gavin, because the world is too harsh a place for tender fools like you.~
@1036 = ~I'm only saying this for your own good. You let things bother you, and they shouldn't. You can't change the world, Gavin, so you're going to have to steel yourself against some of its injustices.~
@1037 = ~I'm not doing either. I know you want to help everyone, and maybe you even think you can. I envy your optimism, but I don't want to see you get hurt.~
@1038 = ~Now why would you think I'm mocking you? Could it be because you never open your mouth except to spout some preachy bilge about the rights of the downtrodden?~
@1039 = ~This conversation is over.~
@1040 = ~I can't do that. I won't do that.~
@1041 = ~People get hurt every day, and so must I.~
@1042 = ~Anyway, I've had this one memory in my head that keeps surfacing to haunt me, and it isn't getting any easier to live with it.~
@1043 = ~Do you want to talk about it?~
@1044 = ~I know you see things that bother you, Gavin, but you're going to have to learn to live with them.~
@1045 = ~We're working toward a greater goal, and we can't afford to lose sight of that.~
@1046 = ~Don't go to pieces on me now, Gavin. I need you focused on *my* plans, not worrying about what you may have done or said in a past life.~
@1047 = ~You're going to have to find a way, because I haven't got time to hold your hand through the rough patches.~
@1048 = ~I'm not sure I can.~
@1049 = ~I don't know if I can.~
@1050 = ~We can't afford to ignore the plight of individuals, either.~
@1051 = ~Then there's nothing left to say.~
@1052 = ~But for all that, I haven't lived the life you've lived, or experienced the nightmares that plague you. So, when memories surface to haunt me, I have no way to shut them out.~
@1053 = ~It's all some kind of slavery. Children are stolen, or bought and sold, prostitutes are treated like property, and everyone just goes on about their lives like nothing's wrong. Some of it is even legal, and that's what really makes me sick.~
@1054 = ~So what are you going to do about it?~
@1055 = ~I know, Gavin. It upsets me, too. We can fight the slavers, at least.~
@1056 = ~I'm sorry you're so upset, but the system works. Some sacrifices must be made to uphold order.~
@1057 = ~I'm telling you, Gavin, the problem is that there are too many rules. If people were left to sort it all out themselves, they wouldn't have the problems they have now.~
@1058 = ~If something is wrong, it isn't the legal system. The strong thrive, the weak do their bidding. This is natural and right.~
@1059 = ~Has anyone ever told you that you think too much?~
@1060 = ~Thank you for telling me what's been bothering you, Gavin. I wish I had the answers, but I don't.~
@1061 = ~There's nothing I can do. Not now.~
@1062 = ~And if we beat them back, more will come to take their place.~
@1063 = ~<CHARNAME>, a woman may have been beaten to death on the street. There is no order.~
@1064 = ~It hasn't been working too well, so far, but there's always hope, always another tomorrow.~
@1065 = ~With some regularity.~
@1066 = ~I don't either, but there's always hope.~
@1067 = ~If there's ever going to be change, it will be because peoples' attitudes have changed, the way they think. Making laws won't work, breaking them won't help. Every person has to believe that better things are possible and that all creatures deserve the chance to grow and prosper.~
@1068 = ~We can guide, but if the change is going to mean anything, it has to come from within.~
@1069 = ~Do you ever think about the friends you left behind?~ [bgav110]
@1070 = ~Which? The ones I had back at Candlekeep or those I met adventuring?~
@1071 = ~Who doesn't? Sometimes, I miss them, but life moves on, and I must, too.~
@1072 = ~My life is so hectic that I don't have time or energy enough to think about the friends I have now!~
@1073 = ~I don't really have a lot of friends.~
@1074 = ~I don't have any friends. Only minions.~
@1075 = ~Either. People you befriended in your past who are no longer with you.~
@1076 = ~I miss them sometimes.~
@1077 = ~With all that's going on in my life, I can't give too much thought to reminiscences.~
@1078 = ~I don't have a lot of friends.~
@1079 = ~The only friends I have are traveling with me now.~
@1080 = ~I understand how that goes. You wonder how they're faring, what has changed in their lives since you last parted company, or whether you'd even know them again.~
@1081 = ~I understand how that goes. Simply surviving from one day to the next takes it out of you.~
@1082 = ~I never know whether you're serious when you talk like that. For my own sanity, I'm going to assume you're not. In any case, I was talking about how people need something in their lives that they can rely on.~
@1083 = ~Ha! Careful, <CHARNAME>, or I'll start thinking you've been letting nefarious forces influence you. Kidding aside, everyone needs someone, some constant in their lives.~
@1084 = ~That's a pity.~
@1085 = ~I'm glad to be counted in that company, then. But in a way, it's unfortunate, because we're all affected by the things that affect you.~
@1086 = ~People need a touchstone, something in their lives that will always be the same, no matter how much their own lives change.~
@1087 = ~That was always Imoen, for me. I could always count on her.~
@1088 = ~Gorion was that for me, but he's gone.~
@1089 = ~I've got you for that. Nothing ever changes your ways.~
@1090 = ~You're here, and you won't change, will you?~
@1091 = ~You'll always be there for me, won't you?~
@1092 = ~I don't know if I need someone for that. I've got my own beliefs, and that's good enough for me.~
@1093 = ~I don't need that. I don't want anything tying me to my past.~
@1094 = ~That's very sentimental of you.~
@1095 = ~You had someone. That's the important thing.~
@1096 = ~Your foster father? He lives on in your memory, though. His constancy will stay with you throughout your life.~
@1097 = ~Not if I can possibly help it, but your regard means a lot.~
@1098 = ~No, I won't, and I'm pleased to hear you say you consider me a constant in your life.~
@1099 = ~As long as I live, my love.~
@1100 = ~Not if I can help it. I'm pleased that you still consider me a constant in your life.~
@1101 = ~No, nothing does.~
@1102 = ~You did. But that's another matter.~
@1103 = ~I'll be honest with you, <CHARNAME>. You hold some beliefs that I hope and pray might one day change.~
@1104 = ~They've kept you from harm so far.~
@1105 = ~That makes me hopeful, somehow.~
@1106 = ~You know best, I suppose, but to me, it seems like you've turned out all right, despite your past.~
@1107 = ~I get that way, sometimes.~
@1108 = ~How are you holding up, <CHARNAME>?~ [bgav111]
@1109 = ~Why do you keep asking me that?~
@1110 = ~There are good days and bad.~
@1111 = ~Never better, why?~
@1112 = ~Stop asking me that, already. You worry more than a mother hen.~
@1113 = ~I'm tired, my head hurts, and your feet stink.~
@1114 = ~Adventuring isn't easy.~
@1115 = ~You do seem to be holding it all together, somehow.~
@1116 = ~I don't know if I can agree with that. There are times when you seem to have trouble holding it all together.~
@1117 = ~You're holding together all right, but I know adventuring isn't easy.~
@1118 = ~As a healer and as a companion, I think I've got the right to worry a bit.~
@1119 = ~My feet stink?~
@1120 = ~Like cheese left outside on a hot day.~
@1121 = ~A bit.~
@1122 = ~So do mine, probably.~
@1123 = ~And you're the child of Bhaal... that must make things tough, sometimes.~
@1124 = ~I'm the master of my own destiny, Gavin. My blood does not rule me.~
@1125 = ~You make much of my taint, but I don't think I'm much different than anyone else.~
@1126 = ~I can feel it, sometimes, like there's this dark core of energy inside me. All that potential, all that power, all waiting for me to find a way to tap it.~
@1127 = ~All anyone ever wants to talk about is my heritage. I'm getting tired of it.~
@1128 = ~And there's something about you... I can't quite identify what it is. It's as if your destiny is greater than the rest of ours, or as if you have powers the rest of us don't.~
@1129 = ~I'm the master of my own destiny, Gavin. Whatever power I may have, I'm the one who decides what to do with it.~
@1130 = ~I don't feel any different than anyone else.~
@1131 = ~I'm the child of Bhaal, Gavin.~
@1132 = ~Right. I guess I know what I'm doing tonight. Now, about that head... the pressure must really be getting to you.~
@1133 = ~(sigh) I guess there's still time for improvement.~
@1134 = ~Good for you! Good for all of us.~
@1135 = ~How would you know?~
@1136 = ~Er... that came out wrong. My point is that you have no reference for comparison. You've never been any other way.~
@1137 = ~That does NOT sound healthy. Resist it, <CHARNAME>... please.~
@1138 = ~It certainly sets you apart. Is it so strange that others would be curious about it?~
@1139 = ~I'm sorry, I don't think I heard you right. I thought you just said you're a child of Bhaal.~
@1140 = ~I'm sorry, Gavin. I should have told you sooner.~
@1141 = ~That's what I said. I'm a Bhaalspawn.~
@1142 = ~You need to clean the wax out of your ears. I said I'm the child of Gaal.~
@1143 = ~You need to clean the wax out of your ears. I said I'm the child of Paal.~
@1144 = ~Sorry, <CHARNAME>, this is a lot to take in all at once. Why didn't you tell me sooner?~
@1145 = ~Because I knew you would treat me differently. As soon as anyone finds out, they treat me like a monster... or worse, a specimen to be studied.~
@1146 = ~It never came up in conversation.~
@1147 = ~It isn't really the kind of thing you announce.~
@1148 = ~The lunatic in the Temple District?~
@1149 = ~Never heard of him.~
@1150 = ~He was a very prominent wizard around here once, known for unorthodox experimentation on prisoners.~
@1151 = ~He was involved in some unusually ruthless business dealings a while back. He's dead, but I don't think his victims would mind revenging themselves upon his kin.~
@1152 = ~You're one of the few, then.~
@1153 = ~He invented the spoon. I never tell anyone for fear that I'll be swarmed by admirers.~
@1154 = ~I can understand that.~
@1155 = ~I would have thought you might have found a reason to bring it up... or maybe not.~
@1156 = ~No, I imagine not.~
@1157 = ~In that case, I can understand your desire to keep your ancestry secret.~
@1158 = ~I'll count myself fortunate, I guess. Your father must have been notorious, if you won't even say what he did.~
@1159 = ~Heh. Fine, keep your secrets.~
@1160 = ~If my reaction was typical, I can only imagine how difficult it must have been for you to find acceptance anywhere.~
@1161 = ~So, what are your plans, going forward?~
@1162 = ~Do whatever good I can... or at least do as little ill as possible.~
@1163 = ~Survive, be strong, and take each day as it comes. Tomorrow has to be better than today.~
@1164 = ~Learn to harness this power, and turn it to my advantage.~
@1165 = ~I have no idea.~
@1166 = ~We can do this. I know we can.~
@1167 = ~Oh, no. There are just so many ways that can go wrong... for yourself as much as everyone else.~
@1168 = ~Neither do I.~
@1169 = ~Where in the nine hells is my shaving mirror?~ [bgav112]
@1170 = ~Where did you have it last?~
@1171 = ~I borrowed it. Here.~
@1172 = ~How should I know?~
@1173 = ~Have you ever thought that just maybe you should grow a beard?~
@1174 = ~Just a moment, Gavin, and I'll help you look for it.~
@1175 = ~If it was up your ass you'd know it.~
@1176 = ~What kind of an answer is that? I'm looking for my mirror, not grooming tips.~
@1177 = ~If I knew that, I wouldn't be looking for it now, would I?~
@1178 = ~You borrowed it. That's just great. How do you shave when you can't take someone else's things?~
@1179 = ~You borrowed it? Why? You don't need to shave. Oh, that's right. Check the hair, check the face, and have I got anything stuck in my teeth? Women. And what do you do when you can't take someone else's things?~
@1180 = ~Well, somebody must, because I sure don't!~
@1181 = ~I don't see what good that will do. I've already looked everywhere.~
@1182 = ~And I suppose you think that's clever. Wise-ass remarks are the last thing I need.~
@1183 = ~And here it is, right on top of your pack. So, did you think you'd just open up my pack, root around a while, and pull out the first thing I'd miss just to jest with me? Or did you just assume you could take anything you like without bothering to ask?~
@1184 = ~That's the problem with you, and with everyone else, it seems. 'There's old Gavin. He's such a sport. He won't mind a little bit of fun.' Or 'He's such a pushover. He won't be fussed if I just help myself to whatever he's got.' Hmf!~
@1185 = ~This really isn't like you, Gavin. Is something wrong?~
@1186 = ~Whoa! Who put salt in your coffee?~
@1187 = ~Gavin, you're scaring me. I've never seen you like this before.~
@1188 = ~It was just a mirror!~
@1189 = ~Oh, that's right! I found it on the ground last night and put it there for safekeeping. I meant to give it back, but I must have forgotten.~
@1190 = ~Aye, something's wrong!~
@1191 = ~Aye, blame it all on me! If there's a problem, it must be my fault!~
@1192 = ~Well, it's about time I stood up for myself.~
@1193 = ~Aye, it's just a mirror. But it's MY mirror.~
@1194 = ~Pft! If you expect me to believe that, you must think me gullible beyond all measure.~
@1195 = ~That's the problem around here. I get no respect. I give and I give, and for what? So everybody can take me for granted.~
@1196 = ~I don't take you for granted, Gavin. You're a valuable member of this group.~
@1197 = ~You're making too much of this.~
@1198 = ~I'm sorry you're so upset, but this is really no way to behave.~
@1199 = ~I'm starting to think that getting involved with you is a bad idea.~
@1200 = ~I'm starting to think that our engagement may be a bad idea.~
@1201 = ~You're right. You don't get any respect, and the reason you don't is because you throw tantrums like this!~
@1202 = ~I'm going to walk away now, and I don't want to talk to you again until you've calmed down.~
@1203 = ~Just shut up. Right now.~
@1204 = ~As long as I do everything you say and never complain. Bah.~
@1205 = ~What? Just because I finally decide to stand up for myself, for a change? Forget it, <CHARNAME>.~
@1206 = ~I'll behave any damn way I want.~
@1207 = ~Yeah? Well, maybe I am, too.~
@1208 = ~My thoughts exactly.~
@1209 = ~You can say that again. I never should have agreed to it in the first place.~
@1210 = ~This isn't a tantrum! Maybe you don't want to hear what I'm saying, but I should have said it a long time ago.~
@1211 = ~Hmf!~
@1212 = ~<CHARNAME>, I need to apologize for my outburst earlier. I know I said some terrible things, and I'm sorry, but I couldn't seem to stop.~ [bgav113]
@1213 = ~We all have bad days.~
@1214 = ~I understand, and I forgive you.~
@1215 = ~That's what happens when you keep everything bottled up. Sooner or later, you're going to blow.~
@1216 = ~I don't know, Gavin. You said some terrible things.~
@1217 = ~You might regret it now, but what is said can never be unsaid.~
@1218 = ~It's too late for apologies now.~
@1219 = ~So, you're not just rude, you're spineless, too. 'Sorry' is for the weak.~
@1220 = ~Maybe, but not everyone makes a capital offense of a misplaced mirror.~
@1221 = ~Thank you, <CHARNAME>.~
@1222 = ~Well, that's certainly what I did earlier.~
@1223 = ~I did, and I should have had better self-control than that.~
@1224 = ~Does that mean...~
@1225 = ~It means that I don't think as highly of you as I once did, and no longer welcome your attention.~
@1226 = ~It means that I no longer want to marry you.~
@1227 = ~It means that I won't be asking you to my bed any time soon, or ever again, for that matter.~
@1228 = ~I'll get over it, but give me some time, alright?~
@1229 = ~Oh, I forgive you, but no more outbursts, please.~
@1230 = ~I know...~
@1231 = ~Hardly. Do you have any idea how difficult it is to apologize? But never mind. I suppose forgiveness isn't in your nature, either.~
@1232 = ~It might be. I've never really thought about it.~
@1233 = ~No, it isn't.~
@1234 = ~I'm surprised to hear you say such a thing. We all need forgiveness, sometimes, but I understand if you aren't quite ready to forgive me yet. I'll just keep hoping that you can soon.~
@1235 = ~Well... thing is...~
@1236 = ~Ah, hells. Can you ever forgive me?~
@1237 = ~I think so. Shake hands?~
@1238 = ~I think so. Shall we kiss and make up?~
@1239 = ~I need some more time.~
@1240 = ~Not this time.~
@1241 = ~Forgiveness is a powerful healer, and I'm grateful.~
@1242 = ~One ill-considered word, and it's all over?~
@1243 = ~I'm sorry, <CHARNAME>. I had no idea...~
@1244 = ~No... I'm sorry.~
@1245 = ~Ah, well, I had hoped it wouldn't be like this, but all things must end.~
@1246 = ~Yes... of course.~
@1247 = ~Well, do so, please. And I'm not just saying that because I want you to forgive me. You'll feel better about yourself, too.~
@1248 = ~Alright, I forgive you.~
@1249 = ~No, I'm not ready for that.~
@1250 = ~Ah, well. I had to try.~
@1251 = ~Gladly! Thank you, <CHARNAME>.~
@1252 = ~(Gavin's lips barely graze yours before he retreats.)~
@1253 = ~I... I'm sorry, <CHARNAME>... I'm just not in the right frame of mind for this.~
@1254 = ~Gladly!~
@1255 = ~(Gavin kisses you soundly, holding you in a close embrace.)~
@1256 = ~Er... yes... if you like.~
@1257 = ~(Gavin's lips brush yours lightly, but he quickly steps away.)~
@1258 = ~Sorry, <CHARNAME>, I wasn't really prepared for a request like that.~
@1259 = ~Er... no, I don't really think that would be appropriate, even under the circumstances.~
@1260 = ~What the hells.~
@1261 = ~(Gavin leans in and kisses you soundly, if self-consciously.)~
@1262 = ~Then time you shall have.~
@1263 = ~Now that that's out of the way, could you help me find my socks?~
@1264 = ~You're hardly the same person you were, when I first joined your company.~ [bgav114]
@1265 = ~Sadder but wiser?~
@1266 = ~I know we've been living under some pretty harsh conditions, but I'd hope I haven't grown ugly yet.~
@1267 = ~Is that supposed to be a compliment?~
@1268 = ~I certainly don't feel like the same person.~
@1269 = ~You're imagining things. I'm still the same person I was.~
@1270 = ~Hardly!~
@1271 = ~You're... mighty! You're more powerful than I would have thought possible, for one.~
@1272 = ~That doesn't say much for your imagination.~
@1273 = ~I knew I could do it. You should have had more faith in me.~
@1274 = ~I knew I could do it. Maybe you just don't believe in me.~
@1275 = ~Does that make you uncomfortable? Some men feel threatened by a powerful woman.~
@1276 = ~I wouldn't have believed it, either.~
@1277 = ~Yet here you are.~
@1278 = ~Not at all! You were always better at everything than me. It's a bit of a thrill, being in the company of someone greater than me, and maybe even being found worthy of notice...~
@1279 = ~You have your charms.~
@1280 = ~So, you're thrilled at being in my company, eh? Does it excite you physically?~
@1281 = ~Er... right.~
@1282 = ~Don't flatter yourself.~
@1283 = ~Not at all! You were always better at everything than me. It's a thrill, being loved by someone greater than me, or even being found worthy of notice...~
@1284 = ~You were always better at everything than me. It's a thrill, pleasuring someone greater than me, having once been found worthy of notice...~
@1285 = ~So, you're physically excited by my power, eh?~
@1286 = ~I'd have thought you'd have noticed... ahem.~
@1287 = ~You have no idea. Ahem.~
@1288 = ~Well, isn't this awkward. Let's go back to talking about you.~
@1289 = ~Er... I'd better not answer that. Let's go back to talking about you. It's far safer.~
@1290 = ~Heh. Well, let's hope you continue to find clumsy priests amusing.~
@1291 = ~You're also loyal, caring, and a good friend.~
@1292 = ~You make me laugh. I like that.~
@1293 = ~And you look good with your shirt off. Don't forget that.~
@1294 = ~I'm hoping you grow out of this awkward phase.~
@1295 = ~Now you're making me blush, so let's go back to talking about you.~
@1296 = ~I'm not sure I like the sound of that, so let's go back to talking about you.~
@1297 = ~No, it isn't like that. It's more...~
@1298 = ~You're more confident, you've become better at your profession, you can do things I wouldn't have thought possible. And while it's no slight on you, it doesn't say much for my own ambition.~
@1299 = ~I've had to work hard to get where I am.~
@1300 = ~You could do more, if you just tried.~
@1301 = ~Sometimes, I wonder what the limits of my abilities even are.~
@1302 = ~That's hard to say.~
@1303 = ~I'm content with the gifts Lathander bestowed on me. He gave me the ability to help others and the desire to do so, so I do what I can. He did not see fit to burden me with pride, and I'm just as happy without it.~
@1304 = ~Are you saying I'm arrogant?~
@1305 = ~I'm happy with some of the other gifts Lathander gave you.~
@1306 = ~Your abilities have been an asset to this group.~
@1307 = ~Whatever.~
@1308 = ~I'm glad I was able to help.~
@1309 = ~You'd better stop that, or the blushing will make me dizzy.~
@1310 = ~But we were talking about you.~
@1311 = ~You've come a long way, in the time I've known you.~
@1312 = ~No, not at all.~
@1313 = ~I know the cost has been heavy for you.~
@1314 = ~It seems like the more I can do, the more I'm expected to do.~
@1315 = ~Too high. I've lost friends, family, any hope of stability, and for what? More responsibilities.~
@1316 = ~It's been worth it, though. Just think of all I can do!~
@1317 = ~I wouldn't have been able to do any of it without help from my friends.~
@1318 = ~We might have helped, but the guiding hand was yours. You paid the price, and you reaped the rewards.~
@1319 = ~It isn't fair that you should have to suffer so much loss, but your sacrifice hasn't been in vain... even if your cares are greater now.~
@1320 = ~That's just the way it goes.~
@1321 = ~It's the way it goes. The more power you have, the more responsibilities you have. More people count on you.~
@1322 = ~So when do I get to be king?~
@1323 = ~So when do I get to be queen?~
@1324 = ~So when do I get to be empress?~
@1325 = ~I don't remember ever being given a choice.~
@1326 = ~I don't mind. At least I know I'm doing something worthwhile.~
@1327 = ~I never asked for it, and I don't want it.~
@1328 = ~No, you weren't ever given a choice, were you?~
@1329 = ~That you are.~
@1330 = ~You are, and that's another thing I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1331 = ~You've made so many changes in your life, you're hardly the <PRO_MANWOMAN> you were, and the change has been for the better. You've grown as a person, and you've become someone I'd be proud to call a friend.~
@1332 = ~It's time to break from the past, to be reborn. Are you ready?~
@1333 = ~I'm ready. I want to be a better person.~
@1334 = ~What do you mean?~
@1335 = ~I need more time to think about it.~
@1336 = ~No, I can't change that much.~
@1337 = ~There's something we need to talk about, though. You know what kind of man I am. I've stayed with you because I hoped that you would change. Maybe you're trying, but I just don't see it happening. I need to know where we stand.~
@1338 = ~I want to change, I really do, but it's hard to do.~
@1339 = ~Then I would have to say that you are ready, after all.~
@1340 = ~I guess that you just aren't ready yet, though I hope that it may happen one day soon.~
@1341 = ~I can't tell you how overjoyed I am that you've embraced this change.~
@1342 = ~If you accept the fact that you aren't the person you were, and choose to continue what you've started, you can become a better person. It really is that simple.~
@1343 = ~Then take the time you need.~
@1344 = ~You know the man I am, though. Some things will have to change.~
@1345 = ~Do you mean you're not ready yet, or do you mean that you never will be ready?~
@1346 = ~I'm not ready yet.~
@1347 = ~I'm not ready, and I never will be.~
@1348 = ~(sigh) I hoped you wouldn't feel that way, but I'll remain in the party, and pray you change your mind.~
@1349 = ~(sigh) I'd really hoped that it wouldn't come down to this, but it has. I'm sorry, <CHARNAME>, but you knew what kind of man I am when I signed on. If I'm to follow my conscience, I can no longer continue in your company. Farewell.~
@1350 = ~Sometimes... Maybe you want to do more. I just don't know. I wish I did, because then I wouldn't have to say what I know that I must.~
@1351 = ~If you need more time, take it, but some things are going to have to change.~
@1352 = ~You never were. No one ever is. Though perhaps that's untrue.~
@1353 = ~You could have just turned your back on everyone who needed you and sought power for your own ends.~
@1354 = ~When I find a vacant throne, I'll let you know.~
@1355 = ~I don't know, but if you do, keep me in mind if you need a jester.~
@1356 = ~You already are, to me.~
@1357 = ~<CHARNAME> the Demigoddess, ruler of worlds. There's a sobering thought.~
@1358 = ~You mean you're not? I thought you must be some kind of royalty, the way you've made me your fool.~
@1359 = ~There's something else I wanted to talk to you about... your attitude is different now than it was when we first met.~
@1360 = ~So, where are we off to now?~ [bgav115]
@1361 = ~Quests, quests, and more quests.~
@1362 = ~We're just finishing a few more things, and then we'll make camp.~
@1363 = ~We're just finishing a few more things, and then we'll find an inn for the night.~
@1364 = ~I don't even know anymore.~
@1365 = ~It never ends. Where's a person supposed to find time for a normal life?~
@1366 = ~That would depend on your definition of normal. This is the only life I've known.~
@1367 = ~Why would I even want a life like that? It sounds boring, if you ask me.~
@1368 = ~It can't be helped, Gavin. We've got things we've got to do, and no one else will do them if we don't.~
@1369 = ~I don't know. It has its appeal.~
@1370 = ~You get up, do whatever work you have to do, come home, kiss your lover, and maybe spend a bit of the evening mending socks or visiting friends.~
@1371 = ~You mend socks?~
@1372 = ~Well, you're lucky, then. Your lover's right here.~
@1373 = ~I can kiss my lover anytime I want.~
@1374 = ~So how is that different from our lives? Except for the 'going home' part, that's pretty much how we live our lives.~
@1375 = ~I like to be different.~
@1376 = ~And you are, but that isn't the point.~
@1377 = ~Well, that isn't really the point.~
@1378 = ~And I'm glad you are, but that isn't the point.~
@1379 = ~Figuratively speaking.~
@1380 = ~My point is that you don't spend the evening slogging through rat-infested dungeons. There were times, back in the old days, when I could go for weeks on end without ever seeing a rat, let alone a troll.~
@1381 = ~Those days are gone forever, Gavin. You might as well get used to it.~
@1382 = ~What? You don't like cold, dark corridors festooned with cobwebs?~
@1383 = ~There are times when I miss that, too, but what can we do? Give up and go home?~
@1384 = ~But it has its good points. There's the treasure, for one.~
@1385 = ~Especially not the cobwebs.~
@1386 = ~Alright, maybe we have to give up the idea of keeping normal hours, but can't we find some balance between what's personal and what's important?~
@1387 = ~Of course we can. We can hold hands whenever we aren't actually in combat.~
@1388 = ~Of course we can. I'll just hold hands with my lover whenever we aren't actually in combat.~
@1389 = ~Maybe we can. We can't just run away leaving everything unfinished, but maybe we can take some time off, go away for a while.~
@1390 = ~Normal is boring. I want no part of it.~
@1391 = ~We can't think about 'personal' at all right now. There are too many lives depending on our decisions.~
@1392 = ~I think you're missing the point.~
@1393 = ~No, Gavin, I think you are. We've got a job to do, and we won't get any rest until it's done.~
@1394 = ~That's pretty blunt.~
@1395 = ~Maybe we could get away for a little while.~
@1396 = ~I think I know how to take your mind off things.~
@1397 = ~You just need to get laid.~
@1398 = ~Sorry, I didn't intend offense. I know we've got a job to do. I just think we need some time to relax, too.~
@1399 = ~We just haven't got time to relax. People are counting on us.~
@1400 = ~I think I just swallowed my tongue.~
@1401 = ~With comments like that, you just did.~
@1402 = ~Well, that just got my undivided attention.~
@1403 = ~It might work for a little while, but the worries always come back.~
@1404 = ~You're right. It isn't time to rest yet, but maybe we can go away for a bit, camp out for one night someplace remote and relatively peaceful.~
@1405 = ~We're in the middle of the woods, Gavin. We'll be camping tonight whether you like it or not.~
@1406 = ~We're in the middle of something now, but we'll go camping next chance we get.~
@1407 = ~I can't make any promises.~
@1408 = ~We'll go where I say we go, understood?~
@1409 = ~I think I'll like that.~
@1410 = ~I'm complaining again, aren't I?~
@1411 = ~Maybe, but you have a reason.~
@1412 = ~No more than usual.~
@1413 = ~No, I understand your point.~
@1414 = ~It's for your sake as well as mine. Spending a day or two in the wilds would do you good. You'll feel better after a restful night under the stars.~
@1415 = ~Do you remember Beregost?~ [bgav116]
@1416 = ~Remember it? I only hope that one day I'll live to forget it!~
@1417 = ~It was the biggest town I had ever seen! Well, until I came to Baldur's Gate.~
@1418 = ~It was there that I met you. I'm not likely to forget it.~
@1419 = ~Only vaguely. I only passed through it a couple of times.~
@1420 = ~Not really. The past runs together, after a while, and it no longer seems so important.~
@1421 = ~I don't remember it as being that unpleasant.~
@1422 = ~It was a small town with muddy streets and bad ale.~
@1423 = ~I don't like any city, really.~
@1424 = ~It wasn't unpleasant, really, just small.~
@1425 = ~We weren't in the city half a day before we got into our first fight. And then there was Marl. Why couldn't he have just left me alone?~
@1426 = ~I was joking, Gavin. I met you there, so I'm bound to remember it.~
@1427 = ~The whole world seemed a lot smaller then. We had fewer cares.~
@1428 = ~'We?' You weren't there.~
@1429 = ~It sure didn't seem that way at the time.~
@1430 = ~Do you think so? I remember being a lot more anxious then than I am now.~
@1431 = ~I'm surprised to hear you speak of the place and the time so fondly, considering the life that you were running from.~
@1432 = ~Nostalgia, Gavin?~
@1433 = ~Ah, but will you remember it well or ill for the association?~
@1434 = ~That all depends on how vexed I am with you at the moment.~
@1435 = ~I thought you the most awkward-looking creature I had ever set eyes on.~
@1436 = ~You were different then, more hesitant and insecure.~
@1437 = ~I remember you tripping over the rut of a wagon wheel and knocking me into a mud puddle, if that's what you mean.~
@1438 = ~Well, I think. You've always been a good friend.~
@1439 = ~Beregost will always be dear to me for that.~
@1440 = ~Are you sure you want to know?~
@1441 = ~I remember it better, but I lived there for sixteen years, if you count the time before my ordination.~
@1442 = ~(yawn) Is this going to be a long story?~
@1443 = ~Well, I met you there, but that's about all I really remember about it.~
@1444 = ~So what did I miss?~
@1445 = ~Is there a reason you're thinking about this now?~
@1446 = ~I know what you mean.~
@1447 = ~Bad ale? The Red Sheaf had the best ale on the Sword Coast!~
@1448 = ~That's right, you did like that place, didn't you?~
@1449 = ~This isn't about ale, though, is it?~
@1450 = ~It was swill, Gavin. You were probably just too drunk to remember it clearly.~
@1451 = ~About all I remember about the Red Sheaf was the dwarf that tried to kill me.~
@1452 = ~No, you don't, do you? But it isn't really about Beregost.~
@1453 = ~Poor Marl. The death of his son hit him hard. He was never what you'd call cheerful. He could find the thundercloud behind any rainbow, but after his son died he gave up on life completely. I know the townspeople blamed you for his death, but I think he was just looking for a way to die.~
@1454 = ~But what else do you remember about the place?~
@1455 = ~I met you there.~
@1456 = ~Not much, really. I was only passing through.~
@1457 = ~Apart from muddy streets and bad ale?~
@1458 = ~Garrick. He was such a sweet, silly boy, with his heart in his hand and his brain in his -~
@1459 = ~Garrick. He was a character, all right, with his heart in his hand and his brain in his -~
@1460 = ~I remember you kissing some prostitutes outside Feldpost's.~
@1461 = ~How much else could there be to remember? The town wasn't very big.~
@1462 = ~But I was, though you didn't know it. I lived there for seven years before I became a Dawnbringer and nine years after. It was time enough for me to get to know the place. But what do you remember about it?~
@1463 = ~Garrick. He was character, all right, with his heart in his hand and his brain in his -~
@1464 = ~It never does. You're stronger now than you were then, so it takes more to make you anxious.~
@1465 = ~If you're saying that someday I'm going to look back on the present as a time of idyllic bliss, I don't want to think about it.~
@1466 = ~When does it end, Gavin? When do we get to look back on the past and think how much better things are now?~
@1467 = ~Actually, I meant that I'm all right. I don't feel the pressure that I used to.~
@1468 = ~That just goes to show that a person can get used to anything.~
@1469 = ~Even you.~
@1470 = ~I would rather not have had to learn that lesson.~
@1471 = ~Or maybe I've just stopped caring.~
@1472 = ~Stress is like pain. Something can only hurt so much before you become numb.~
@1473 = ~How are you holding up?~
@1474 = ~I wasn't running from anything... maybe I was. I wanted a second chance, an opportunity to leave the past behind and forge ahead with people who knew nothing of me or my problems. Needless to say, that didn't work. I could never abandon Lanie, in any case, but the lie of my silence got too heavy to bear.~
@1475 = ~And then there was you to think about. I couldn't hide my past from you and I found that I didn't want to try.~
@1476 = ~It feels like a lifetime ago, or like it happened to someone else. When I think about the petty things that used to keep me awake at night with worry... well, these days, I wish that was all we had to worry about.~
@1477 = ~I wouldn't have pegged you for a worrier.~
@1478 = ~Me, too.~
@1479 = ~You hid your concern well. From your snores, I never would have guessed that anxiety kept you awake.~
@1480 = ~So what keeps you awake now?~
@1481 = ~You worry too much. Things aren't that bad, really.~
@1482 = ~I'm a trial to you, I know. But that isn't what I was thinking about, at the moment.~
@1483 = ~I'm not surprised. You never think about how much you irritate those around you.~
@1484 = ~All right, what were you thinking about?~
@1485 = ~I was teasing you, Gavin.~
@1486 = ~I hate to say it, but this isn't the best time for a conversation.~
@1487 = ~And now?~
@1488 = ~Some things never change.~
@1489 = ~Oh, you're still a mess, but I wouldn't have it any other way.~
@1490 = ~You're more confident these days, but you'll always be Gavin.~
@1491 = ~As long as you're quick with the healing spells, you can stagger your way from here to Icewind Dale.~
@1492 = ~Why are you so worried about what I think?~
@1493 = ~Now I think you're pretty alright.~
@1494 = ~I love you, Gavin. What more is there to say?~
@1495 = ~Well, I do value your opinion.~
@1496 = ~You're fine the way you are.~
@1497 = ~I love you just the way you are.~
@1498 = ~I've learned to expect very little.~
@1499 = ~We all have our faults.~
@1500 = ~I need you to think less about my opinion and more about your responsibilities in this party.~
@1501 = ~Just my luck you'd have such a good memory. Regardless, that wasn't what I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1502 = ~It warms my heart to hear you say that, but that wasn't what I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1503 = ~I thank you, but that wasn't what I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1504 = ~Wonderful. But that wasn't what I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1505 = ~You're still as charming as always... but that wasn't what I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1506 = ~Nothing, really. Nothing happens in Beregost. That's part of its charm. But that wasn't what I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1507 = ~I've been thinking a lot about the past lately.~
@1508 = ~You? I thought Lathandrites lived for 'tomorrow,' not 'yesterday.'~
@1509 = ~And what conclusion have you reached?~
@1510 = ~I'd like you to think more about the present, especially where it concerns your doing your job in this party.~
@1511 = ~And you said this wouldn't be a long story.~
@1512 = ~I have, too. I'm looking for answers, but they're hard to find.~
@1513 = ~I did. It was almost like a second home... or a first home, after Miranda and I fell out. But that wasn't what I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1514 = ~Perhaps... The Red Sheaf was almost like a second home... or a first home, after Miranda and I fell out. But that wasn't what I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1515 = ~One does tend to remember assassins... though you seem to have had more than your share of those. But that wasn't what I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1516 = ~Ahem... er.. yes, I believe I remember him. But that wasn't what I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1517 = ~True. I don't see how it could get much worse... though I hope that doesn't mean that I simply lack imagination. But that isn't what I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1518 = ~It was only one prostitue, she kissed me, and she did it because I treated her like a human being instead of a trade item. But that isn't what I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1519 = ~Soon, I hope. But that isn't what I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1520 = ~So, you're used to me, eh? Be careful. That's one step shy of abhorrence. But that wasn't what I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1521 = ~After everything you have been through, do you still think you get to choose your lessons? But never mind. I had nothing so profound on my mind today, though I did wish to speak with you.~
@1522 = ~Do you really mean that?~
@1523 = ~No, not really. Sometimes, I wish I did, though.~
@1524 = ~Yes, unfortunately. It's too much, Gavin. Too many people expect me to solve their problems for them.~
@1525 = ~I don't know what to think, anymore. If I help this person, then that person must suffer. Too many choices.~
@1526 = ~I don't want to talk about it. What were you going to say?~
@1527 = ~You can't say something like that and expect me to let it drop.~
@1528 = ~Look, I said I don't want to talk about it and I meant it.~
@1529 = ~I was exaggerating, all right?~
@1530 = ~I'm tired, Gavin. I've been fighting the good fight all this time, and I'm weary.~
@1531 = ~Think about it. We slave away, risking our lives time and again, and for what? The chance at a shallow, unmarked grave? I'm done with being the hero.~
@1532 = ~Me? My faith keeps me going, so I'll be fine.~
@1533 = ~Enough about me, though. There was something I wanted to talk to you about.~
@1534 = ~Usually, I'm not, but you face troubles that most people don't, and I can't help but be concerned. But that wasn't what I wanted to talk to you about, at least this time.~
@1535 = ~There are times... and you face troubles that most people don't, so I can't help but be concerned. But that wasn't what I wanted to talk to you about, at least this time.~
@1536 = ~I am, where you're concerned. You face troubles that most people don't, and I worry that you'll be alright. But that wasn't what I wanted to talk to you about, at least this time.~
@1537 = ~Perhaps I did. Never mind that, though.~
@1538 = ~Never mind about that, for the time being.~
@1539 = ~You, if I'm lucky, but never mind about that, for the time being.~
@1540 = ~Would you like me to go?~
@1541 = ~No, you do have your uses.~
@1542 = ~If I ever make up my mind, you'll be the first to know.~
@1543 = ~Perish the thought!~
@1544 = ~It might be for the best.~
@1545 = ~Never mind, then.~
@1546 = ~It isn't as if I could be someone else if I tried.~
@1547 = ~I was remembering life before any of this, when the worst thing that I could expect at the end of any given day was to come home and find that Miranda had taken off again or that the crows had raided the garden.~
@1548 = ~Every morning, I'd go to the temple before dawn, celebrate the sunrise, then go do whatever work I had to do that day. At the end of it, if all was well at home, I'd put Lanie on my knee and we'd build castles out of twigs or tell each other stories until it was time for her to go to bed.~
@1549 = ~Sometimes, if Miranda was in for the night, I'd head over to the Red Sheaf for a quiet pint and a bit of gossip.~
@1550 = ~I never realized how much I would miss those days.~
@1551 = ~I'd have been bored out of my skull.~
